# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: howstuffworks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] The 24/7 News service began in 1999 as an audio news wire service when Clear Channel launched the Total Traffic and Weather Network subsidiary.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] It has 22 local news bureaus in 12 key cities.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] The service began streaming on its own webcast channel in 2008 when Clear Channel launched the iHeartRadio platform.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] In 2012, TTWN/iHeart began soft-launched the 24/7 News radio network featuring national and local news provided by iHeart's TTWN and Metro Networks subsidiaries, syndicated to most of iHeart-owned stations in key large and medium-sized markets.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] On July 11, 2016, NBCUniversal licensed the name "NBC News Radio" to iHeartMedia, using talent and reporters from iHeartMedia's existing 24/7 News Network, made available to the group's approximately 850 radio stations.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] The reintroduced service included an hourly newscast along with ancillary specials and longform breaking news coverage.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] In 2024, the webcast channel and podcast has been reverted to the 24/7 News brand.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] However, the webcast/podcast will continue to use news reports outsourcing from NBC News.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] 24/7 News provides top- and bottom-hour newscast on both terrestrial/syndication, webcast and podcast, using sources from NBC News and iHeart's own TTWN subsidiary.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] Similar to Westwood One News, iHeart uses the unbranded version of the newscast for radio stations.
[src:howstuffworks/24-7-news] In addition, the network's online webcast also streams major breaking news/developing story and special events, such as State of the Union speech and election coverage (although both are outsourced from ABC News Live).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] The ***Atlanta Business Chronicle*** is a weekly newspaper covering business news in Atlanta, Georgia, published by American City Business Journals.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] The paper has both a weekly print edition and an online edition.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] The *Atlanta Business Chronicle* was founded in 1978 by Bob Gray and Mike Weingart.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] Gray, the publisher, and Weingart, the newspaper's first editor, had previously founded the *Houston Business Journal*.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] In 1980, the company Scripps Howard (now E.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] Scripps Company) bought the Cordovan Corporation, which owned the *Atlanta Business Chronicle* and other business newspapers.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] From 1980 to 1983, Carol Carter served as the paper's editor.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] In 1986, the *paper* was sold to American City Business Journals.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] In 1988, the *Atlanta Business Chronicle* was the first to break the major story that the Sumitomo Life Insurance Company was buying the IBM Tower (One Atlantic Center) for $300 million.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] At the time, the editor of the paper was Anita Sharpe.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] Under Sharpe, two Gerald Loeb Awards were won by the paper for investigative reporting.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] In the 1990s, the *Atlanta Business Chronicle* was also first to report many major stories, such as the ventures of the ISP MindSpring (now EarthLink) and communications company Scientific Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] Other first stories included the introduction of the 770 telephone area code to Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] Annually, the *Atlanta Business Chronicle* gives out awards for "40 under 40," which is 40 people under the age of 40 who are professionals that have demonstrated leadership and social responsibility in Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-business-chronicle] The *Atlanta Business Chronicle* has a paid circulation of 23,275, along with 729,899 monthly online readers.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] On January 8, 2019, the podcast released a second season.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] Titled ***Monster: Zodiac***, the second season explored the Zodiac murders.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] In January 2020, they launched a third season titled ***Monster: DC Sniper***.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] The first season of the series explores the child murders that occurred in Atlanta during 1979-1981 and the mystery behind who was the culprit of all those killings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] Besides discussing the topic of the crime, the series also explores the underlying racial tensions and separation between the white and black citizens of Atlanta at the time as the victims were all black children.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] The series also looks at the way the city and country reacted to the murders and the way the media portrayed the victims.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] The podcast takes a look into the way the investigation was handled, whether the suspect they caught was the real culprit, and the way the Black and white community remembered the incident differently.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-monster] Later seasons explore other regions and times where serial killers were known to be on the loose.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The **Atlanta murders of 1979–1981**, sometimes called the **Atlanta child murders**, are a series of murders committed in Atlanta, Georgia, United States between July 1979 and May 1981.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Over the two-year period, at least 28 African-American children, adolescents, and adults were killed.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Wayne Williams, an Atlanta native who was 23 years old at the time of the last murder, was arrested, tried, and convicted of two of the adult murders and sentenced to two consecutive life terms.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In March 2019, the Atlanta police, under the order of Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms, reopened the cases in hopes that new technology would lead to a conviction for the murders that were never resolved.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] As of November 2025, no results have been made public.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Investigator Chet Dettlinger created a map of the victims' locations.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Despite the difference in ages, the victims fell within the same geographic parameters.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] They were connected to Memorial Drive and 11 major streets in the area.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Author Ginger Strand links the murders to freeway racism and Atlanta's massive urban renewal program that disrupted African American neighborhoods.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] There were significant delays in beginning an investigation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] During the murders, more than 100 agents were working on the investigation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The city of Atlanta imposed curfews, and parents in the city removed their children from school and forbade them from playing outside.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] As the media coverage of the killings intensified, the FBI predicted that the killer might dump the next victim into a body of water to conceal any evidence.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Police staked out nearly a dozen area bridges, including crossings of the Chattahoochee River.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] During a stakeout on May 22, 1981, detectives got their first major break when an officer heard a splash beneath a bridge.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Another officer saw a white 1970 Chevrolet station wagon turn around and drive back across the bridge.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Two police cars later stopped the suspect station wagon about a half-mile from the bridge.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The driver was 23-year-old Wayne Bertram Williams, a supposed music promoter and freelance photographer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The Chevrolet wagon belonged to his parents.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] During questioning, Williams said he was on his way to audition a woman, Cheryl Johnson, as a singer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Williams claimed she lived in the nearby town of Smyrna.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Police did not find any record of her or the appointment.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Two days later, on May 24, the nude body of Nathaniel Cater, 27, was found floating downriver a few miles from the bridge where police had seen the suspicious station wagon.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Based on this evidence, including the police officer's hearing of the splash, police believed that Williams had killed Cater and disposed of his body while the police were nearby.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Investigators who stopped Williams on the bridge noticed gloves and a 24-inch nylon cord sitting in the passenger seat.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] According to investigators, the cord looked similar to ligature marks found on Cater and other victims, but the cord was never taken into evidence for analysis.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Adding to a growing list of suspicious circumstances, Williams had handed out flyers in predominantly black neighborhoods calling for young people ages 11–21 to audition for his new singing group that he called Gemini.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Williams failed an FBI-administered polygraph examination, though polygraph results are not admissible as evidence in criminal courts.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Fibers from a carpet in the Williams residence were found to match those observed on two of the victims.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Additional fibers from the Williams's home, vehicles, and pet dog were later matched to fibers discovered on other victims.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Furthermore, witness Robert Henry claimed to have seen Williams holding hands and walking with Nathaniel Cater on the night Cater is believed to have died.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On June 21, 1981, Williams was arrested.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] A grand jury indicted him for first-degree murder in the deaths of Nathaniel Cater and Jimmy Ray Payne, aged 22.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] When the news of Williams' arrest was officially released (his status as a suspect had previously been leaked to the media), FBI Agent John E.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Douglas stated that, if it was Williams, then he was "looking pretty good for a good percentage of the killings." Douglas had previously conducted an interview with *People* magazine about profiling the killer as a young black man.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] This was widely reported as the FBI effectively declaring Williams guilty, and Douglas was officially censured by the Director of the FBI.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Jury selection began on December 28, 1981, and it lasted six days.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Nine women and three men comprised the jury, among which were eight African Americans and four Caucasians.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The trial officially began on January 6, 1982, with Judge Clarence Cooper presiding.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The most important evidence against Williams was the fiber analysis between the victims he was indicted for murdering, Jimmy Ray Payne and Nathaniel Cater, and the 12 pattern-murder cases in which circumstantial evidence culminated in numerous links between the crimes.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] This evidence included witnesses who testified that they had seen Williams with the victims, and some witnesses suggested that he had solicited sexual favors.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The prosecution's presentation of the case has been criticized, to the extent that in some jurisdictions it might have resulted in a mistrial.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] After reviewing the case, Georgia Supreme Court Justice George T.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Smith deemed the evidence, or the lack thereof, inadmissible.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On February 27, 1982, after 11 hours of deliberation, the jury found Wayne Bertram Williams guilty of the two murders.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] He was sentenced to two consecutive life terms in Georgia's Hancock State Prison in Sparta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Allegedly, a family of Klan members living outside of Atlanta had hoped to ignite a race war in Atlanta, and attempted to recruit others for this purpose.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Sanders, a narcotics dealer and recruiter for the group, was said to have told a criminal informant he intended to kill Geter several weeks before his body was found.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] After Geter had backed a go-cart into his car, Sanders allegedly told the informant "I'm gonna kill that black bastard.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The article reported that in 1981, members of the GBI and officials in other law enforcement agencies opted to close their investigation and seal their findings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] A handwritten transcript of a conversation between Klan members regarding Geter's murder was sent anonymously to Lynn Whatley in 1985, an attorney who was then representing Wayne Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] At a 1991 hearing on Williams' request for a new trial, wherein he was represented by attorneys Alan Dershowitz, William Kunstler, and Bobby Lee Cook, investigators from both Atlanta and Georgia law-enforcement agencies testified they had little or no knowledge of the GBI's investigation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] At the same hearing, an informant for the GBI reported that in 1981, Charles Sanders had admitted to killing Geter while Whitaker was wearing a concealed microphone.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Graham, one of the original investigators in these cases, said he doubted that Wayne Williams, the man convicted of two of the killings and blamed for 22 others, was guilty of all of them.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On June 21, 2006, the DeKalb County Police dropped its re-investigation of the Atlanta child murders.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On January 29, 2007, attorneys for the State of Georgia agreed to allow DNA testing of the dog hair that was used to help convict Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] This decision was in response to a legal filing as a part of Williams' efforts to appeal his conviction and life sentences.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Williams' lawyer, Jack Martin, asked a Fulton County Superior Court judge to allow DNA tests on canine and human hair and blood, stating that the results might help Williams win a new trial.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On June 26, 2007, the DNA test results showed that the hairs on the bodies contained the same mitochondrial DNA sequence as Williams' dog — a sequence that occurs in only about 1 out of 100 dogs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Later in 2007, the FBI performed DNA tests on two human hairs found on one of the victims.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The mitochondrial DNA sequence in the hairs would eliminate 99.5% of persons by not matching their DNA, and would eliminate 98% of African American persons by not matching their DNA.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] However, they matched Williams' DNA, thus not eliminating the possibility that the hairs were his.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On March 21, 2019, Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms and Atlanta Police Chief Erika Shields announced that officials would re-test evidence from the murders, which would be gathered by the Atlanta Police Department, Fulton County District Attorney's Office, and Georgia Bureau of Investigation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In a news conference, Mayor Bottoms said, "It may be there is nothing left to be tested.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In July 2021, Bottoms announced that DNA had been identified and sampled in two cases that would be subjected to additional analysis by a private lab.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Investigators combed through 40% of the original DNA evidence and had sent that to the same private lab for testing on June 21, 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] As of December 2022, no results have been made public, despite requests from the victims' families.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] As of 2019, Wayne Williams continued to maintain his innocence.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The first national media coverage of the case was in 1980, when a team from ABC News *20/20*, Stanhope Gould and Bill Lichtenstein, producer Steve Tello, and correspondent Bob Sirkin from the ABC Atlanta bureau looked into the case.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In a week, the team reported on the dead and missing children, and they broke the story that the Atlanta Police Task Force was not writing down or following up on every lead they received through the police hotline that had been set up.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In 1981, British novelist Martin Amis published "The Killings in Atlanta" for *The Observer*, later compiled into *The Moronic Inferno: And Other Visits to America* (1986).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] While the demon is ultimately vanquished, the story ends on an ominous note criticizing the social inequalities that made the non-white children such attractive targets, as well as children's television shows that encourage blind trust of strangers.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In 1985, the television miniseries *The Atlanta Child Murders* was released.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] It was centered around the murders and the arrest of the suspect.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] It revolved mainly around the aftermath of the killings and the trials.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] It starred Calvin Levels, Morgan Freeman, James Earl Jones, Rip Torn, Jason Robards, Martin Sheen, and Bill Paxton.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Atlanta officials criticized the film, claiming that it distorted the facts of the case.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] After a series of negotiations, CBS executives agreed to insert a disclaimer alerting viewers that the film is based on fact but contains fictional elements.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Also in 1985, James Baldwin published *The Evidence of Things Not Seen*, a non-fiction examination not only of the case and Williams' trial, but also of race relations in Atlanta and, by extension, America.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The book grew out of an assignment to write about the murders for *Playboy*, commissioned by then-editor Walter Lowe.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In his 1995 book *Mindhunter: Inside the FBI's Elite Serial Crime Unit*, criminal profiler John E.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Douglas said that, while he believes that Williams committed many of the murders, he does not think that he committed them all.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In 2000, Showtime released a drama film titled *Who Killed Atlanta's Children?* starring James Belushi and Gregory Hines.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In 2002, Tayari Jones published the novel *Leaving Atlanta*.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] It focuses on the lives and experiences of three fictional fifth graders at Oglethorpe Elementary School, Tasha Baxter, Rodney Green, and Octavia Fuller, during the murder spree.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] During the time of the murders, Jones attended Oglethorpe Elementary School and was classmates with two of the real-life victims, Yusuf Bell and Terry Pue.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] On June 10, 2010, CNN broadcast a documentary, *The Atlanta Child Murders*, with interviews by Soledad O'Brien with some of the people involved, including Wayne Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In the 2016 song "the ends" by American rapper Travis Scott featuring American rapper André 3000, on the former's second studio album, *Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight*, Atlanta-native André 3000 raps about the killings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In January 2018, documentary filmmaker Payne Lindsey began releasing a podcast called *Atlanta Monster*, covering the murders with interviews from family members of victims, law enforcement officials, individuals alive in the Atlanta area at the time of the murders, and Wayne Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The second season of *Mindhunter* (released in August 2019) covers the murders.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] The series, which is focused on the history of the FBI's Behavioral Science Unit (BSU) builds a dramatic arc of the series over the FBI's two BSU agents who join the Atlanta investigation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In the series fictional treatment, Agent Ford has the role of insisting that 13 murders they are investigating at the time are the work of one single serial killer, and that in order to gain the victims' trust, he may be African-American himself.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] This line of deduction clashes with that of his colleague Agent Tench, the Atlanta Police Department, and the African-American community of Atlanta – many of whom believe, in light of Georgia's history of hate crimes and racial violence, that the killings are the work of the Ku Klux Klan.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] In April 2020, HBO released a 5-part documentary titled *Atlanta's Missing and Murdered: The Lost Children,* directed by Sam Pollard and Maro Chermayeff.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] HBO's documentary revealed information that focused heavily on the appeals process of the case against Wayne Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Williams' attorneys filed a habeas corpus document and it was denied.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-murders-of-1979-81] Similarly, his request for a retrial was denied in 2004.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta was originally founded as the terminus of a major state-sponsored railroad, but soon became the convergence point for several railroad lines, spurring its rapid growth.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The largest of these was the Western and Atlantic Railroad, from which the name "Atlanta" is derived, reflecting the city's growing reputation as a major transportation hub.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the American Civil War, the city served a strategically important role for the Confederacy.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] It was captured in 1864 following the Atlanta campaign, and under Union General William T.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Sherman, Atlanta was almost entirely burned to the ground during the March to the Sea.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta rebounded dramatically in the post–Civil War period and quickly became a national industrial center and the unofficial capital of the "New South".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] After World War II, Atlanta emerged as a manufacturing and technology hub.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, it became a major organizing center of the American civil rights movement, with Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph Abernathy, and many other locals serving as prominent leaders.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the modern era, Atlanta has remained a major transportation center, with Hartsfield-Jackson International Airport becoming the world's busiest airport by passenger traffic in 1998.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] It has maintained this position every year since, except in 2020, with an estimated 93.7 million passengers in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] With a nominal gross domestic product (GDP) of $473 billion in 2021, Atlanta has the 11th-largest economy among U.S. cities and the 22nd-largest in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Its economy is diverse, with dominant sectors including transportation, aerospace, logistics, healthcare, news and media operations, film and television production, information technology, finance, biomedical research, and public policy.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta established itself on the world stage when it won the bid to host the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Games had a lasting impact on Atlanta's development into the 21st century, leading to significant investment in the city's universities, parks, and tourism industry.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The gentrification of some of its neighborhoods has intensified in the 21st century with the growth of the Atlanta Beltline rail trail, altering Atlanta's demographics, politics, aesthetics, and culture.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] For thousands of years prior to the arrival of European settlers in North Georgia, the indigenous Creek people, Cherokee people, and their ancestors inhabited the area.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Standing Peachtree, a Creek village where Peachtree Creek flows into the Chattahoochee River, was the closest Native American settlement to what is now Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Through the early 19th century, European Americans systematically encroached on the Creek of northern Georgia, forcing them out of the area from 1802 to 1825.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Creek were forced to leave the area in 1821, under Indian Removal by the federal government, and European American settlers arrived the following year.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 1836, the Georgia General Assembly voted to build the Western and Atlantic Railroad in order to provide a link between the port of Savannah and the Midwest.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The initial route was to run southward from Chattanooga to a terminus east of the Chattahoochee River, which would be linked to Savannah.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] After engineers surveyed various possible locations for the terminus, the "zero milepost" was driven into the ground in what is now Foundry Street, Five Points.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] When asked in 1837 about the future of the little village, Stephen Harriman Long, the railroad's chief engineer said the place would be good "for one tavern, a blacksmith shop, a grocery store, and nothing else".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] A year later, the area around the milepost had developed into a settlement, first known as *Terminus*, and later *Thrasherville*, after a local merchant who built homes and a general store in the area.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] By 1842, the town had six buildings and 30 residents and was renamed *Marthasville* to honor Governor Wilson Lumpkin's daughter Martha.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Later, John Edgar Thomson, Chief Engineer of the Georgia Railroad, suggested the town be renamed *Atlanta*, supposedly a feminine version of the word "Atlantic", referring to the Western and Atlantic Railroad.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] (Atalanta was also Martha Lumpkin's middle name.) The residents approved, and the town was incorporated as Atlanta on December 29, 1847.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] By 1860, Atlanta's population had grown to 9,554.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the American Civil War, the nexus of multiple railroads in Atlanta made the city a strategic hub for the distribution of military supplies.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 1864, the Union Army moved southward following the capture of Chattanooga and began its invasion of north Georgia.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The region surrounding Atlanta was the location of several major army battles, culminating with the Battle of Atlanta and a four-month-long siege of the city by the Union Army under the command of General William Tecumseh Sherman.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On September 1, 1864, Confederate General John Bell Hood decided to retreat from Atlanta, and he ordered the destruction of all public buildings and possible assets that could be of use to the Union Army.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On the next day, Mayor James Calhoun surrendered Atlanta to the Union Army, and on September 7, Sherman ordered the city's civilian population to evacuate.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On November 11, 1864, Sherman prepared for the Union Army's March to the Sea by ordering the destruction of Atlanta's remaining military assets.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] After the Civil War ended in 1865, Atlanta was gradually rebuilt during the Reconstruction era.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Due to the city's superior rail transportation network, the state capital was moved from Milledgeville to Atlanta in 1868.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the 1880 Census, Atlanta had surpassed Savannah as Georgia's largest city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Grady, the editor of the *Atlanta Constitution* newspaper, promoted Atlanta to potential investors as a city of the "New South" that would be based upon a modern economy and less reliant on agriculture.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] By 1885, the founding of the Georgia School of Technology (now the Georgia Institute of Technology) and the Atlanta University Center, a consortium of historically black colleges made up of units for men and women, had established Atlanta as a center for higher education.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 1895, Atlanta hosted the Cotton States and International Exposition, which attracted nearly 800,000 attendees and successfully promoted the New South's development to the world.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the first decades of the 20th century, Atlanta enjoyed a period of unprecedented growth.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In three decades' time, Atlanta's population tripled as the city limits expanded to include nearby streetcar suburbs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city's skyline grew taller with the construction of the Equitable, Flatiron, Empire, and Candler buildings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Sweet Auburn emerged as a center of Black commerce.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The period was also marked by strife and tragedy.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Increased racial tensions led to the Atlanta Race Riot of 1906, when Whites attacked Blacks, leaving at least 27 people dead and over 70 injured, with extensive damage in Black neighborhoods.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 1913, Leo Frank, a Jewish-American factory superintendent, was convicted of the murder of a 13-year-old girl in a highly publicized trial.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] He was sentenced to death, but the governor commuted his sentence to life.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] An enraged and organized lynch mob took him from jail in 1915 and hanged him in Marietta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Jewish community in Atlanta and across the country were horrified.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On May 21, 1917, the Great Atlanta Fire destroyed 1,938 buildings in what is now the Old Fourth Ward, resulting in one fatality and the displacement of 10,000 people.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On December 15, 1939, Atlanta hosted the premiere of *Gone with the Wind*, the epic film based on the best-selling novel by Atlanta's Margaret Mitchell.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The gala event at Loew's Grand Theatre was attended by the film's legendary producer, David O.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Selznick, and the film's stars Clark Gable, Vivien Leigh, and Olivia de Havilland, but Oscar winner Hattie McDaniel, an African-American actress, was barred from the event due to racial segregation laws.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta played a vital role in the Allied effort during World War II.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Colonel Blake Van Leer, the president of Georgia Tech, played a significant part by lobbying war-related manufacturing companies like Lockheed Martin to move to Atlanta, successfully lobbying the Government to build military bases, in turn helping attract thousands of new residents through new jobs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Van Leer also launched major research centers, which included Neely Nuclear Research Center and funds to help make Georgia Tech the "MIT" of the south while also founding Southern Polytechnic State University.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] These new defense industries attracted thousands of new residents and generated revenues, resulting in rapid population and economic growth.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the 1950s, the city's newly constructed highway system, supported by federal subsidies, allowed middle-class Atlantans the ability to relocate to the suburbs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] As a result, the city began to make up an ever-smaller proportion of the metropolitan area's population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] African-American veterans returned from World War II seeking full rights in their country and began heightened activism.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In exchange for support by that portion of the Black community that could vote, in 1948 the mayor ordered the hiring of the first eight African-American police officers in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Much controversy preceded the 1956 Sugar Bowl, when the Pitt Panthers, with African-American fullback Bobby Grier on the roster, met the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] There had been controversy over whether Grier should be allowed to play due to his race, and whether Georgia Tech should even play at all due to Georgia's Governor Marvin Griffin's opposition to racial integration.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] After Griffin publicly sent a telegram to the state's Board of Regents requesting Georgia Tech not to engage in racially integrated events, Georgia Tech's president Blake R.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Van Leer rejected the request and threatened to resign.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Later, students from both Georgia Tech and the University of Georgia held a protest against Griffin's stance, which soon turned into a riot.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The students broke windows, upturned parking meters, hung Griffin in effigy, and marched all the way to the governor's mansion, surrounding it until 3:30 a.m.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Griffin publicly blamed Georgia Tech's president for the "riots" and requested he be replaced and Georgia Tech's state funding be cut off.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On December 5 the Georgia Tech board of regents voted 13–1 in favor of allowing the game to proceed as scheduled.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the 1960s, Atlanta became a major organizing center of the civil rights movement, with Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph Abernathy, and students from Atlanta's historically black colleges and universities playing major roles in the movement's leadership.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] While Atlanta in the postwar years had relatively minimal racial strife compared to other cities, Blacks were limited by discrimination, segregation, and continued disenfranchisement of most voters.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Desegregation of the public sphere came in stages, with public transportation desegregated by 1959, the restaurant at Rich's department store by 1961, movie theaters by 1963, and public schools by 1973 (nearly 20 years after the U.S.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Supreme Court ruled that segregated public schools were unconstitutional).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 1960, Whites comprised 61.7% of the city's population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the 1950s–70s, suburbanization and White flight from urban areas led to a significant demographic shift.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] By 1970, African Americans were the majority of the city's population and exercised their recently enforced voting rights and political influence by electing Atlanta's first Black mayor, Maynard Jackson, in 1973.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Under Mayor Jackson's tenure, Atlanta's airport was modernized, strengthening the city's role as a transportation center.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The opening of the Georgia World Congress Center in 1976 further confirmed Atlanta's rise as a convention city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Construction of the city's subway system began in 1975, with rail service commencing in 1979.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Despite these improvements, Atlanta lost more than 100,000 residents between 1970 and 1990, over 20% of its population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] At the same time, it developed new office space after attracting numerous corporations, with an increasing portion of workers from northern areas.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta was selected as the site for the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Following the announcement, the city government undertook several major construction projects to improve Atlanta's parks, sporting venues, and transportation infrastructure; however, for the first time, none of the $1.7 billion cost of the games was governmentally funded.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] While the games experienced transportation and accommodation problems and the Centennial Olympic Park bombing occurred despite extra security precautions, the spectacle was still a watershed event in Atlanta's history.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] According to former Mayor Kasim Reed, the Olympic Games generated "a direct economic impact of at least USD 5 billion".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, every one of the record 197 national Olympic committees invited to compete sent athletes, sending more than 10,000 contestants participating in a record 271 events.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The related projects, such as Atlanta's Olympic Legacy Program and civic efforts, initiated a fundamental transformation of the city in the following decade.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the 2000s, the city of Atlanta underwent a profound physical, cultural, and demographic change.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] As some of the African-American middle and upper classes also began to move to the suburbs, a booming economy drew numerous new migrants from other cities in the United States, who contributed to changes in the city's demographics.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] African Americans made up a decreasing portion of the population, from a high of 67% in 1990 to 54% in 2010.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] From 2000 to 2010, Atlanta gained 22,763 white residents, 5,142 Asian residents, and 3,095 Hispanic residents, while the city's Black population decreased by 31,678.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Much of the city's demographic change during the decade was driven by young, college-educated professionals: from 2000 to 2009, the three-mile radius surrounding Downtown Atlanta gained 9,722 residents aged 25 to 34 and holding at least a four-year degree, an increase of 61%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] This was similar to the tendency in other cities for young, college educated, single or married couples to live in downtown areas.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the lead-up to the 1996 Summer Olympics, the Atlanta Housing Authority demolished nearly all of its public housing.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Residents instead received vouchers to pay for private housing; a wave of mixed housing was built using funding from the HOPE VI program under CEO Renee Lewis Glover (1994–2013).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 2005, the city approved the $2.8 billion Beltline project.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] It was intended to convert a disused 22-mile freight railroad loop that surrounds the central city into an art-filled multi-use trail and light rail transit line, which would increase the city's park space by 40%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The project stimulated retail and residential development along the loop, but has been criticized for its adverse effects on some Black communities.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 2013, the project received a federal grant of $18 million to develop the southwest corridor.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Cox Foundation gave $6 million to the PATH Foundation which will connect the Silver Comet Trail to The Atlanta Beltline, which was expected to be completed by 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Upon completion, the total combined interconnected trail distance around Atlanta for the Atlanta Beltline and Silver Comet Trail will be the longest paved trail surface in the U.S., totaling about 300 miles (480 km).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta's cultural offerings expanded during the 2000s: the High Museum of Art doubled in size; the Alliance Theatre won a Tony Award; and art galleries were established on the once-industrial Westside.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The College Football Hall of Fame relocated to Atlanta and the National Center for Civil and Human Rights museum was constructed.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city of Atlanta was the subject of a massive cyberattack which began in March 2018.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In December 2019, Atlanta hosted the Miss Universe 2019 pageant competition.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] On June 16, 2022, Atlanta was selected as a host city for the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta encompasses 134.0 square miles (347.1 km2), of which 133.2 square miles (344.9 km2) is land and 0.85 square miles (2.2 km2) is water.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city is situated in the Deep South of the southeastern United States among the foothills of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] At 1,050 feet (320 m) above mean sea level, Atlanta has the highest elevation among major cities east of the Mississippi River.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta straddles the Eastern Continental Divide.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Rainwater that falls on the south and east side of the divide flows into the Atlantic Ocean, while rainwater on the north and west side of the divide flows into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta developed on a ridge south of the Chattahoochee River, which is part of the ACF River Basin.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The river borders the far northwestern edge of the city, and much of its natural habitat has been preserved, in part by the Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta is 21 miles (34 km) southeast of Marietta, 27 miles (43 km) southwest of Alpharetta, 146 miles (235 km) southwest of Greenville, South Carolina, 147 miles (237 km) east of Birmingham, Alabama, and 245 miles (394 km) southwest of Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Despite having lost significant tree canopy coverage between 1973 and 1999, Atlanta now has the densest urban tree coverage of any major city in the United States and is often called "City of Trees" or "The City in a Forest".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta is divided into 242 officially defined neighborhoods.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city contains three major high-rise districts, which form a north–south axis along Peachtree: Downtown, Midtown, and Buckhead.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Surrounding these high-density districts are leafy, low-density neighborhoods, most of which are dominated by single-family homes.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Downtown contains the most office space in the metro area, much of it occupied by government entities.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Downtown is home to the city's sporting venues and many of its tourist attractions.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Midtown is the city's second-largest business district, containing the offices of many of the region's law firms.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Midtown is known for its art institutions, cultural attractions, institutions of higher education, and dense form.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Buckhead, the city's uptown district, is eight miles (13 km) north of Downtown and the city's third-largest business district.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The district is marked by an urbanized core along Peachtree Road, surrounded by suburban single-family neighborhoods situated among woods and rolling hills.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Surrounding Atlanta's three high-rise districts are the city's low- and medium-density neighborhoods, where the craftsman bungalow single-family home is dominant.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The eastside is marked by historic streetcar suburbs, built from the 1890s to the 1930s as havens for the upper middle class.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] These neighborhoods, many of which contain their own villages encircled by shaded, architecturally distinct residential streets, include the Victorian Inman Park, Bohemian East Atlanta, and eclectic Old Fourth Ward.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In southwest Atlanta, neighborhoods closer to downtown originated as streetcar suburbs, including the historic West End, while those farther from downtown retain a postwar suburban layout.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] These include Collier Heights and Cascade Heights, historically home to most of the city's upper middle-class African-American population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Northwest Atlanta contains the areas of the city to west of Marietta Boulevard and to the north of Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Drive, including those neighborhoods remote to downtown, such as Riverside, Bolton and Whittier Mill.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The latter is one of Atlanta's designated Landmark Historical Neighborhoods.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Vine City, though technically Northwest, adjoins the city's Downtown area and has recently been the target of community outreach programs and economic development initiatives.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Gentrification of the city's neighborhoods is one of the more controversial and transformative forces shaping contemporary Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The gentrification of Atlanta has its origins in the 1970s, after many of Atlanta's neighborhoods had declined and suffered the urban decay that affected other major American cities in the mid-20th century.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] When neighborhood opposition successfully prevented two freeways from being built through the city's east side in 1975, the area became the starting point for Atlanta's gentrification.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] After Atlanta was awarded the Olympic Games in 1990, gentrification expanded into other parts of the city, stimulated by infrastructure improvements undertaken in preparation for the games.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] New development post-2000 has been aided by the Atlanta Housing Authority's eradication of the city's public housing.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] As noted above, it allowed the development of these sites for mixed-income housing, requiring developers to reserve a considerable portion for affordable housing units.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] It has also provided for other former residents to be given vouchers to gain housing in other areas.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Construction of the Beltline has stimulated new and related development along its path.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Most of Atlanta was burned in the final months of the American Civil War, depleting the city of a large stock of its historic architecture.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Yet architecturally, the city had never been traditionally "southern": Atlanta originated as a railroad town rather than a southern seaport dominated by the planter class, such as Savannah or Charleston.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Because of its later development, many of the city's landmarks share architectural characteristics with buildings in the Northeast or Midwest, as they were designed at a time of shared national architectural styles.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] During the late 20th century, Atlanta embraced the global trend of modern architecture, especially for commercial and institutional structures.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Examples include the State of Georgia Building, built in 1966, and the Georgia-Pacific Tower in 1982.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Many of the most notable examples from this period were designed by world-renowned Atlanta architect John Portman.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Most of the buildings that define the downtown skyline were designed by Portman during this period, including the Westin Peachtree Plaza and the Atlanta Marriott Marquis.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the latter half of the 1980s, Atlanta became one of the early homes of postmodern buildings that reintroduced classical elements to their designs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Many of Atlanta's tallest skyscrapers were built in this period and style, displaying tapering spires or otherwise ornamented crowns, such as One Atlantic Center (1987), 191 Peachtree Tower (1991), and the Four Seasons Hotel Atlanta (1992).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Also completed during the era was the Bank of America Plaza, built in 1992.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] At 1,023 feet (312 m), it is the tallest building in the city and the 14th-tallest in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city's embrace of modern architecture has often translated into an ambivalent approach toward historic preservation, leading to the destruction of many notable architectural landmarks.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the mid-1970s, the Fox Theatre, now a cultural icon of the city, would have met the same fate if not for a grassroots effort to save it.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] More recently, preservationists may have made some inroads.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] For example, in 2016 activists convinced the Atlanta City Council not to demolish the Atlanta-Fulton Central Library, the last building designed by noted architect Marcel Breuer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Under the Köppen classification, Atlanta has a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) with generous precipitation year-round, typical for the Upland South.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city is situated in USDA Plant Hardiness Zone 8a, with the northern and western suburbs, as well as part of Midtown transitioning to 7b.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with temperatures somewhat moderated by the city's elevation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Winters are overall mild but variable, occasionally susceptible to snowstorms even if in small quantities on several occasions, unlike the central and southern portions of the state.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Warm air from the Gulf of Mexico can bring spring-like highs while strong Arctic air masses can push lows into the teens °F (−7 to −12 °C).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] July averages 80.9 °F (27.2 °C), with high temperatures reaching 90 °F (32 °C) on an average of 47 days per year, though 100 °F (38 °C) readings are not seen most years.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] January averages 44.8 °F (7.1 °C), with temperatures in the suburbs slightly cooler due largely to the urban heat island effect.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Lows at or below freezing can be expected 36 nights annually, but the last occurrences of temperatures below 10 °F (−12 °C) were December 24, 2022, and January 2014, eight years apart.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Average dewpoints in the summer range from 63.7 °F (17.6 °C) in June to 67.8 °F (19.9 °C) in July.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Typical of the southeastern U.S., Atlanta receives abundant rainfall that is evenly distributed throughout the year, though late spring and early fall are somewhat drier.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The average annual precipitation is 50.43 in (1,281 mm), while snowfall is typically light and rare, with a normal of 2.2 inches (5.6 cm) per winter.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The heaviest single snowfall occurred on January 23, 1940, with around 10 inches (25 cm) of snow.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] However, ice storms usually cause more problems than snowfall does, the most severe occurring on January 7, 1973.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Tornadoes are rare in the city itself, but the March 14, 2008, EF2 tornado damaged prominent structures in downtown Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The 2020 United States census reported that Atlanta had a population of 498,715.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The population density was 3,685.45 persons per square mile (1,422.95/km2).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The racial and ethnic makeup of Atlanta (including Hispanics) was 51.0% Black or African American, 40.9% non-Hispanic white, 4.2% Asian, and 0.3% Native American, and 1.0% from other races.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] 2.4% of the population reported two or more races.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Hispanics and Latinos of any race made up 6.0% of the city's population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $77,655 in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The per capita income for the city was $60,778 in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Approximately 17.7% percent of the population was living below the poverty line in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Circa 2024, of the Atlanta residents, 391,711 of them lived in Fulton County and 28,292 of them lived in DeKalb County.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the 1920s, the Black population began to grow in Southern metropolitan cities like Atlanta, Birmingham, Houston, and Memphis.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Since the 1970s, Atlanta has been widely recognized as a hub of African American political activism, education, entrepreneurship, and culture—earning it the reputation of being a Black mecca.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] However, in the 1990s, Atlanta started to experience Black flight.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] African Americans have moved outside the city seeking a lower cost of living or better public schools.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The African American share of Atlanta's population has declined faster than any other racial group.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city's share of Black residents shrank from 67% in 1990 to 47% in 2020.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Blacks made up nine percent of new Atlanta residents between 2010 and 2020.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] At the same time, Atlanta is home to a sizable foreign-born Black population, notably from Eritrea, Ethiopia, Ghana, Somalia, Liberia, and Nigeria.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] With many notable investments occurring in Atlanta initiated by the 1996 Summer Olympics, the non-Hispanic White population of Atlanta began to rebound after several decades of White flight to Atlanta's suburbs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Between 2000 and 2020, the proportion of Whites in the city had strong growth.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In two decades, Atlanta's White population grew from 33% to 39% of the city's population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Whites made up the majority of new Atlanta residents between 2010 and 2020.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Hispanic and Latino populations in Metro Atlanta have experienced significant growth.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The largest Hispanic ancestries in Atlanta are Mexican, Puerto Rican and Cuban.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] There is a growing population of Mexican ancestry throughout the region, with notable concentrations along the Buford Highway and I-85 corridor, and now extending into Gwinnett County.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 2013, Metro Atlanta had the 19th largest Hispanic population in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Atlanta area also has a fast growing Asian American population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The largest groups of Asian origin are those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Pakistani and Japanese descent.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Pew Research Center ranks the Atlanta area among the top 10 U.S. metropolitan areas by Indian population in 2019.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Early immigrants in the Atlanta area were mostly Jews and Greeks.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Since 2010, the Atlanta area has experienced notable immigration from India, China, South Korea, and Jamaica.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Other notable source countries of immigrants are Vietnam, Eritrea, Nigeria, the Arabian gulf, Ukraine and Poland.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Within a few decades, and in keeping with national trends, immigrants from England, Ireland, and German-speaking central Europe were no longer the majority of Atlanta's foreign-born population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city's Italians included immigrants from northern Italy, many of whom had been in Atlanta since the 1890s; more recent arrivals from southern Italy; and Sephardic Jews from the Isle of Rhodes, which Italy had seized from Turkey in 1912.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Europeans from Great Britain, Ireland and Germany settled in the city as early as the 1840s.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Most of Atlanta's European population is from the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Vietnamese people, Cambodians, Ethiopians, and Eritreans were the earliest refugees formally brought to the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Of the total population five years and older, 83.3% spoke only English at home, while 8.8% spoke Spanish, 3.9% another Indo-European language, and 2.8% an Asian language.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Among them, 7.3% of Atlantans were born abroad (86th in the U.S.).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta's dialect has traditionally been a variation of Southern American English.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Chattahoochee River long formed a border between the Coastal Southern and Southern Appalachian dialects.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Because of the development of corporate headquarters in the region, attracting migrants from other areas of the country, by 2003, *Atlanta* magazine concluded that Atlanta had become significantly "de-Southernized".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] A Southern accent was considered a handicap in some circumstances.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In general, Southern accents are less prevalent among residents of the city and inner suburbs and among younger people; they are more common in the outer suburbs and among older people.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] At the same time, some residents of the city speak in Southern variations of African-American English.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta has a diverse lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] According to a 2006 survey by the Williams Institute, Atlanta ranked third among major American cities, behind San Francisco and slightly behind Seattle, with 12.8% of the city's total population identifying as LGB.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Midtown and Cheshire Bridge areas have historically been the epicenters of LGBT culture in Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta formed a reputation for being a place inclusive to LGBT people after former mayor Ivan Allen Jr. dubbed it "the city too busy to hate" in the 1960s (referring to racial relations).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta has consistently scored 100% on the Human Rights Campaign's Municipal Equality Index that measures how inclusive a city's laws, policies and services are for LGBT people who live or work there.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Religion in Atlanta, while historically centered on Protestant Christianity, now encompasses many faiths, as a result of the city and metro area's increasingly international population.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Some 63% of residents identified as some type of Protestant according to the Pew Research Center in 2014, but in recent decades the Roman Catholic Church has increased in numbers and influence because of new migrants to the region.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Metro Atlanta also has numerous ethnic or national Christian congregations, including Korean and Indian churches.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The larger non-Christian faiths according to both studies are Judaism, Islam, and Hinduism.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Overall, there are over 1,000 places of worship within Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] With a GDP of $385 billion, the Atlanta metropolitan area's economy is the 8th-largest in the country and the 15th-largest in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Corporate operations play a major role in Atlanta's economy, as the city claims the nation's third-largest concentration of Fortune 500 companies (tied for third with Chicago).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Over 75% of Fortune 1000 companies conduct business operations in the city's metro area, and the region hosts offices of over 1,250 multinational corporations.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Many corporations are drawn to the city by its educated workforce; as of 2014, 45% of adults aged 25 or older residing in the city have at least four-year college degrees, compared to the national average of 28%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta was born as a railroad town, and logistics continue to represent an important part of the city's economy to this day.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In 2021, major freight railroad Norfolk Southern moved their headquarters to Atlanta, and the city hosts major classification yards for Norfolk Southern and CSX.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport is the world's busiest airport, and the headquarters of Delta Air Lines.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Delta operates the world's largest airline hub at Hartsfield-Jackson and is metro Atlanta's largest employer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] UPS, the world's largest courier company, operates an air cargo hub at Hartsfield-Jackson, and has their headquarters in neighboring Sandy Springs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Media is also an important aspect of Atlanta's economy.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] In the 1980s, media mogul Ted Turner founded the Cable News Network (CNN), Turner Network Television (TNT), HLN (HLN), Turner Classic Movies (TCM), The Cartoon Network, Inc. and its namesake television network, TruTV (truTV) and the Turner Broadcasting System (TBS) in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Around the same time, Cox Enterprises, now the nation's third-largest cable television service and the publisher of over a dozen American newspapers, moved its headquarters to the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Notable sports networks headquartered in Atlanta include TNT Sports, NBA TV, Bally Sports South, and Bally Sports Southeast.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The Weather Channel is also based just outside of the city in suburban Cobb County.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Information technology (IT) has become an increasingly important part of Atlanta's economic output, earning the city the nickname the "Silicon peach".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] As of 2013, Atlanta contains the fourth-largest concentration of IT jobs in the U.S., numbering 85,000+.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city is also ranked as the sixth fastest-growing for IT jobs, with an employment growth of 4.8% in 2012 and a three-year growth near 9%, or 16,000 jobs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Companies are drawn to Atlanta's lower costs and educated workforce.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Recently, Atlanta has been the center for film and television production, largely because of the Georgia Entertainment Industry Investment Act, which awards qualified productions a transferable income tax credit of 20% of all in-state costs for film and television investments of $500,000 or more.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Film and television production facilities based in Atlanta include Techwood Studios, Pinewood Atlanta Studios, Tyler Perry Studios, Williams Street Productions, and the Cinespace Film Studios soundstages.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Film and television production injected $9.5 billion into Georgia's economy in 2017, with Atlanta garnering most of the projects.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] Atlanta has emerged as the all-time most popular destination for film production in the United States and one of the 10 most popular destinations globally.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] As of 2026, Atlanta was designated the best city in the nation for young professionals to start a career using two categories: professional opportunities and quality of life.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p01] The city was also ranked 12th best for starting a new business.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has drawn residents from many other parts of the U.S., in addition to many recent immigrants to the U.S. who have made the metropolitan area their home, establishing Atlanta as the cultural and economic hub of an increasingly multi-cultural metropolitan area.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] This unique cultural combination reveals itself in the arts district of Midtown, the quirky neighborhoods on the city's eastside, and the multi-ethnic enclaves found along Buford Highway.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is one of few United States cities with permanent, professional, and resident companies in all major performing arts disciplines: opera (Atlanta Opera), ballet (Atlanta Ballet), orchestral music (Atlanta Symphony Orchestra), and theater (the Alliance Theatre).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta attracts many touring Broadway acts, concerts, shows, and exhibitions catering to a variety of interests.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's performing arts district is concentrated in Midtown Atlanta at the Woodruff Arts Center, which is home to the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Alliance Theatre.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city frequently hosts touring Broadway acts, especially at The Fox Theatre, a historic landmark among the highest-grossing theaters of its size.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] As a national center for the arts, Atlanta is home to significant art museums and institutions.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The renowned High Museum of Art is arguably the South's leading art museum.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Museum of Design Atlanta (MODA) and the SCAD FASH Museum of Fashion + Film are the only such museums in the Southeast.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Contemporary art museums include the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center and the Museum of Contemporary Art of Georgia.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] A recent arts addition is known as The Warehouse, a storage facility that was turned into a world-class art gallery featuring more than 400 works of art collected over more than 40 years.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The collection is open to the public for free.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Institutions of higher education contribute to Atlanta's art scene, with the Savannah College of Art and Design's Atlanta campus providing the city's arts community with a steady stream of curators.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Carlos Museum contains the largest collection of ancient art in the Southeast.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Spelman College Museum of Fine Art is the only museum in the nation to focus on art by women of the African diaspora.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Williams Museum of Papermaking features the largest collection of paper and paper-related artifacts in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has become one of the U.S.'s best cities for street art in recent years.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] It is home to Living Walls, an annual street art conference and the Outerspace Project, an annual event series that merges public art, live music, design, action sports, and culture.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Examples of street art in Atlanta can be found on the Atlanta Street Art Map.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is home to the nationally known Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, whose music directors have included Robert Shaw (1967–1988), Yoel Levi (1988–2000), Robert Spano (2001–2021), and Nathalie Stutzmann (2022–present).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The orchestra presents a season-long series of concerts including prominent world soloists such as pianists Kirill Gerstein, Yeol Eum Son, Inon Barnatan, Lang Lang, Francesco Piemontesi, cellist Alisa Weilerstein, singer Andrea Bocelli and many others.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has played a major or contributing role in the development of various genres of American music at different points in the city's history.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Beginning as early as the 1920s, Atlanta emerged as a center for country music, which was brought to the city by migrants from Appalachia.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] During the countercultural 1960s, Atlanta hosted the Atlanta International Pop Festival, with the 1969 festival taking place more than a month before Woodstock and featuring many of the same bands.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] During the 1980s, Atlanta had an active punk rock scene centered on two of the city's music venues, 688 Club and the Metroplex, and Atlanta famously played host to the Sex Pistols' first U.S. show, which was performed at the Great Southeastern Music Hall.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The 1990s saw the city produce major mainstream acts across many different musical genres.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Country music artist Travis Tritt, and R&B sensations Xscape, TLC, Usher and Toni Braxton, were just some of the musicians who call Atlanta home.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In the 2000s, Atlanta was recognized by the Brooklyn-based *Vice* magazine for its indie rock scene, which revolves around the various live music venues found on the city's alternative eastside.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] To facilitate further local development, the state government provides qualified businesses and productions a 15% transferable income tax credit for in-state costs of music investments.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] As the national leader for motion picture and television production, and a top ten global leader, Atlanta plays a significant role in the entertainment industry.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is home to the Tyler Perry Studios which is one of the largest film production studios in the U.S.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] It was announced in 2022 a film about the 1956 Sugar Bowl and '56 Atlanta riots would be produced here.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's festival season stretches from January through November.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has more festivals than any city in the southeastern United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] As of 2010, Atlanta is the seventh-most visited city in the United States, with over 35 million visitors per year.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Although the most popular attraction among visitors to Atlanta is the Georgia Aquarium, and until 2012, the world's largest indoor aquarium, Atlanta's tourism industry is mostly driven by the city's history museums and outdoor attractions.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta contains a notable number of historical museums and sites, including the Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] National Historical Park, which includes the preserved childhood home of Dr.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] President Jimmy Carter's papers and other material relating to the Carter administration and the Carter family's life; and the Margaret Mitchell House and Museum, where Mitchell wrote the best-selling novel *Gone with the Wind*.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta contains several outdoor attractions.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Botanical Garden, adjacent to Piedmont Park, is home to the 600-foot-long (180 m) Kendeda Canopy Walk, a skywalk that allows visitors to tour one of the city's last remaining urban forests from 40 feet (12 m) above the ground.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Canopy Walk is the only canopy-level pathway of its kind in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Zoo Atlanta, in Grant Park, accommodates over 1,300 animals representing more than 220 species.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Home to the nation's largest collections of gorillas and orangutans, the zoo is one of only four zoos in the U.S. to house giant pandas.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Festivals showcasing arts and crafts, film, and music, including the Atlanta Dogwood Festival, the Atlanta Film Festival, and Music Midtown, respectively, are also popular with tourists.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Tourists are drawn to the city's culinary scene, which comprises a mix of urban establishments garnering national attention, ethnic restaurants serving cuisine from every corner of the world, and traditional eateries specializing in Southern dining.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Since the turn of the 21st century, Atlanta has emerged as a sophisticated restaurant town.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Many restaurants opened in the city's gentrifying neighborhoods have received praise at the national level, including Bocado, Bacchanalia, and Miller Union in West Midtown, Empire State South in Midtown, and Two Urban Licks and Rathbun's on the east side.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2011, *The New York Times* characterized Empire State South and Miller Union as reflecting "a new kind of sophisticated Southern sensibility centered on the farm but experienced in the city".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Visitors seeking to sample international Atlanta are directed to Buford Highway, the city's international corridor, and suburban Gwinnett County.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] There, the nearly-million immigrants that make Atlanta home have established various authentic ethnic restaurants representing virtually every nationality on the globe.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] For traditional Southern fare, one of the city's most famous establishments is The Varsity, a long-lived fast food chain and the world's largest drive-in restaurant.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Mary Mac's Tea Room and Paschal's are more formal destinations for Southern food.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is best known for its barbecue, hamburgers, Southern fried chicken, and lemon pepper wings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Buford Highway (immediately northeast of Atlanta) is home to many authentic ethnic cuisines such as Mexican and Asian foods.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's culinary landscape is highlighted by its inclusion in the prestigious Michelin Guide, featuring several restaurants recognized for their exceptional cuisine and premier dining destination in the Southeast.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's rapidly expanding food scene is marked by a notable diversity, particularly with the increasing variety and number of Indian restaurants across the city and its metropolitan area, including Chai Pani, a Michelin Guide restaurant.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Sports are an important part of the culture of Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city is home to professional franchises for four major team sports: the Atlanta Braves of Major League Baseball, the Atlanta Hawks of the National Basketball Association, the Atlanta Falcons of the National Football League, and Atlanta United FC of Major League Soccer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In addition, many of the city's universities participate in collegiate sports.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city also regularly hosts international, professional, and collegiate sporting events.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Originally established as the Boston Red Stockings in 1871, they are the oldest continually operating professional sports franchise in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Braves franchise overall has won eighteen National League pennants and four World Series championships in three different cities, with their first in 1914 as the Boston Braves, in 1957 as the Milwaukee Braves, and in 1995 and 2021 as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The 1995 title occurred during an unprecedented run of 14 straight divisional championships from 1991 to 2005.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The team plays at Truist Park, having moved from Turner Field for the 2017 season.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The new stadium is outside the city limits, located 10 miles (16 km) northwest of downtown in the Cumberland/Galleria area of Cobb County.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Falcons have played in Atlanta since their inception in 1966.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The team plays its home games at Mercedes-Benz Stadium, having moved from the Georgia Dome in 2017.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] They have been unsuccessful in both of their Super Bowl trips, losing to the Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII in 1999 and to the New England Patriots in Super Bowl LI in 2017, the largest comeback in Super Bowl history.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2019, Atlanta also briefly hosted an Alliance of American Football team, the Atlanta Legends, but the league was suspended during its first season and the team folded.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Hawks were founded in 1946 as the Tri-Cities Blackhawks, playing in Moline, Illinois.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Louis in 1968 and play their games in State Farm Arena.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Dream of the Women's National Basketball Association shared an arena with the Hawks for most of their existence; however the WNBA team moved to a smaller arena in the southern Atlanta suburb of College Park in 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Professional soccer has been played in some form in Atlanta since 1967.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's first professional soccer team was the Atlanta Chiefs of the original North American Soccer League, which won the 1968 NASL Championship and defeated English first division club Manchester City F.C. twice in international friendlies.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 1998, the Atlanta Silverbacks were formed, playing the new North American Soccer League.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] They now play as an amateur club in the National Premier Soccer League.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2017, Atlanta United FC began play as Atlanta's first premier-division professional soccer club since the Chiefs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] They won MLS Cup 2018, defeating the Portland Timbers 2–0.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Fan reception has been very positive; the team has broken several single-game and season attendance records for both MLS and the U.S.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The club is estimated by Forbes to be the most valuable club in Major League Soccer.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The United States Soccer Federation moved their headquarters from Chicago to Atlanta in 2023 with the help of Falcons and Atlanta United owner Arthur Blank, with the new training center bearing his name.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta will receive a NWSL team in 2028.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In ice hockey, Atlanta has had two National Hockey League franchises, both of which relocated to a city in Canada after playing in Atlanta for fewer than 15 years.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Flames (now the Calgary Flames) played from 1972 to 1980, and the Atlanta Thrashers (now the Winnipeg Jets) played from 1999 to 2011.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Gladiators, a minor league hockey team in the ECHL, have played in the Atlanta suburb of Duluth since 2003.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The ASUN Conference moved its headquarters to Atlanta in 2019.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Several other emerging sports also have professional franchises in Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Georgia Swarm compete in the National Lacrosse League.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Vibe compete in the Pro Volleyball Federation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has long been known as the "capital" of college football in America.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] It is home to four-time national champion Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football and the Georgia State Panthers.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Other annual college football events include the Aflac Kickoff Game, the Celebration Bowl, the MEAC/SWAC Challenge, and the Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl which is one of College Football's major New Year's Six Bowl games and a College Football Playoff bowl.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta additionally hosted the 2018 College Football Playoff National Championship and eventually would the host the 2025 event in the city as well.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta regularly hosts a variety of sporting events.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Most famous was the Centennial 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city has hosted the Super Bowl three times: Super Bowl XXVIII in 1994, Super Bowl XXXIV in 2000, and Super Bowl LIII in 2019.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In professional golf, The Tour Championship, the final PGA Tour event of the season, is played annually at East Lake Golf Club.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2001 and 2011, Atlanta hosted the PGA Championship, one of the four major championships in men's professional golf, at the Atlanta Athletic Club.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2011, Atlanta hosted professional wrestling's annual WrestleMania.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In soccer, Atlanta has hosted numerous international friendlies and CONCACAF Gold Cup matches.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city has hosted the NCAA Final Four Men's Basketball Championship five times, most recently in 2020.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta will serve as one of the eleven US host cities for the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Every summer, Atlanta hosts the Atlanta Open, a men's professional tennis tournament.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Running is a popular local sport, and the city declares itself to be "Running City USA".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city hosts the Peachtree Road Race, the world's largest 10 km race, annually on Independence Day.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta also hosts the nation's largest Thanksgiving day half marathon, which starts and ends at Center Parc Stadium.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Marathon, which starts and ends at Centennial Olympic Park, routes through many of the city's historic landmarks.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's 343 parks, nature preserves, and gardens cover 3,622 acres (14.66 km2), which amounts to only 5.6% of the city's total acreage, compared to the national average of just over 10%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] However, 77% of Atlantans live within a 10-minute walk of a park, a percentage slightly better than the national average of 76%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In its 2023 ParkScore ranking, The Trust for Public Land reported that among the park systems of the 100 most populous U.S. cities, Atlanta's park system received a ranking of 28.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Piedmont Park, in Midtown, is Atlanta's most iconic green space.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The park, which underwent a major renovation and expansion in recent years, attracts visitors from across the region and hosts cultural events throughout the year.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Shirley Clarke Franklin Park, a 280-acre green space and reservoir, opened in 2021 and is the city's largest park.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area, in the northwestern corner of the city, preserves a 48 mi (77 km) stretch of the river for public recreation opportunities.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Botanical Garden, adjacent to Piedmont Park, contains formal gardens, including a Japanese garden and a rose garden, woodland areas, and a conservatory that includes indoor exhibits of plants from tropical rainforests and deserts.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Beltline, a former rail corridor that forms a 22 mi (35 km) loop around Atlanta's core, has been transformed into a series of parks, connected by a multi-use trail, increasing Atlanta's park space by 40%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta offers resources and opportunities for amateur and participatory sports and recreation.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Golf and tennis are popular in Atlanta, and the city contains six public golf courses and 182 tennis courts.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Facilities along the Chattahoochee River cater to watersports enthusiasts, providing the opportunity for kayaking, canoeing, fishing, boating, or tubing.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city's only skate park, a 15,000 square feet (1,400 m2) facility that offers bowls, curbs, and smooth-rolling concrete mounds, is at Historic Fourth Ward Park.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has a reputation as a "city in a forest" due to an abundance of trees that is rare among major cities.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city's main street is named after a tree, and beyond the Downtown, Midtown, and Buckhead business districts, the skyline gives way to a dense canopy of woods that spreads into the suburbs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city is home to the Atlanta Dogwood Festival, an annual arts and crafts festival held one weekend during early April, when the native dogwoods are in bloom.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The nickname is factually accurate, as vegetation covers 47.9% of the city as of 2017, the highest among all major American cities, and well above the national average of 27%.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta's tree coverage does not go unnoticed—it was the main reason cited by *National Geographic* in naming Atlanta a "Place of a Lifetime".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city's lush tree canopy, which filters out pollutants and cools sidewalks and buildings, has increasingly been under assault from man and nature due to heavy rains, drought, aged forests, new pests, and urban construction.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] A 2001 study found Atlanta's heavy tree cover declined from 48% in 1974 to 38% in 1996.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Community organizations and the city government are addressing the problem.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Trees Atlanta, a non-profit organization founded in 1985, has planted and distributed over 113,000 shade trees in the city, and Atlanta's government has awarded $130,000 in grants to neighborhood groups to plant trees.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Fees are additionally imposed on developers that remove trees on their property per a citywide ordinance, active since 1993.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is governed by a mayor and the 15-member Atlanta City Council.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city council consists of one member from each of the city's 12 districts and three at-large members.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The mayor may veto a bill passed by the council, but the council can override the veto with a two-thirds majority.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The mayor of Atlanta is Andre Dickens, a Democrat elected on a nonpartisan ballot whose first term in office began on January 3, 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Every mayor elected since 1973 has been Black.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2001, Shirley Franklin became the first woman to be elected mayor of Atlanta, and the first African-American woman to serve as mayor of a major Southern city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta city politics suffered from a notorious reputation for corruption during the 1990s administration of Mayor Bill Campbell, who was convicted by a federal jury in 2006 on three counts of tax evasion in connection with gambling winnings during trips he took with city contractors.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] As the state capital, Atlanta is the site of most of Georgia's state government.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Georgia State Capitol building, located downtown, houses the offices of the governor, lieutenant governor, and secretary of state, as well as the General Assembly.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Governor's Mansion is in a residential section of Buckhead.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta serves as the regional hub for many arms of the federal bureaucracy, including the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The City of Atlanta annexed the CDC into its territory effective January 1, 2018.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta also plays an important role in the federal judiciary system, containing the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit and the United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Historically, Atlanta has been a stronghold for the Democratic Party.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Although municipal elections are officially nonpartisan, nearly all of the city's elected officials are registered Democrats.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city is split among 14 state house districts and four state senate districts, all held by Democrats.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] At the federal level, Atlanta is split between three congressional districts.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Most of the city is in the 5th district, represented by Democrat Nikema Williams.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Much of southern Atlanta is in the 13th district, whose seat is currently vacant following the death of Democrat David Scott.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] A small portion in the north is in the 11th district, represented by Republican Barry Loudermilk.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city is served by the Atlanta Police Department (APD), which numbers 2,000 officers and oversaw a 40% decrease in the city's crime rate between 2001 and 2009.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2012, *Forbes* ranked Atlanta as the 6th most dangerous American city, but by 2023, the city dropped out of its top 10.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Despite some improvement in crime, street gangs have continued to plague the city since the 1980s.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2022, there was a 200% increase in gang-related charges in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2023, Money Inc named Atlanta the third worst gang city in the U.S.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Also in 2023, it was estimated that about 1,000 gangs in the Atlanta area were responsible for at least 70% of all crime including identity theft, credit card fraud, drug trafficking, and human trafficking.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Georgia Bureau of Investigation Gang Task Force in partnership with the APD is leading efforts in dismantling gang activity and arresting culprits.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Fire Rescue Department provides fire protection and first responder emergency medical services to the city from its 35 fire stations.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2017, AFRD responded to over 100,000 calls for service over a coverage area of 135.7 square miles (351.5 square kilometers).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The department also protects Hartsfield–Jackson with five fire stations on the property, serving over 1 million passengers from over 100 countries.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The department protects over 3000 high-rise buildings, 23 miles (37 kilometers) of the rapid rail system, and 60 miles (97 kilometers) of interstate highway.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Georgia National Guard is based in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Emergency ambulance services are provided to city residents by hospital-based Grady EMS (Fulton County), and American Medical Response (DeKalb County).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In January 2017, Atlanta declared itself a "welcoming city" and "will remain open and welcoming to all".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Nonetheless, Atlanta does not consider itself to be a "sanctuary city".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms said: "Our city does not support ICE.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] We don't have a relationship with the U.S.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2025, Atlanta Public Safety Training Center opened a $118 million training center for police and firefighters.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] With more than 15 colleges and universities, including three law schools and two medical schools, Atlanta is considered one of the nation's largest hubs for higher education.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Three universities have earned the highest classification of "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Georgia Institute of Technology, commonly referred to as Georgia Tech, is a prominent public research university in Midtown.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] It offers highly ranked degree programs in engineering, design, industrial management, the sciences, business, and architecture.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is home to nationally renowned private colleges and universities, most notably Emory University, a leading liberal arts and research institution that operates Emory Healthcare, the largest health care system in Georgia.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The City of Atlanta annexed Emory into its territory effective January 1, 2018.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta University Center is also in the city; it is the nation's only contiguous consortium of historically black colleges, comprising Spelman College, Clark Atlanta University, Morehouse College, and Morehouse School of Medicine.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta contains a campus of the Savannah College of Art and Design, a private art and design university that has proven to be a major factor in the recent growth of Atlanta's visual art community.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta also boasts American Bar Association accredited law schools: Atlanta's John Marshall Law School, Emory University School of Law, and Georgia State University College of Law.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The University of Georgia's Terry College of Business operates a satellite campus in Atlanta's Buckhead district, a major financial center in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] This location facilitates Executive and Professional MBA programs plus executive education offerings.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Buckhead campus also serves as a hub where Terry students, alumni, faculty, and staff can engage with the business community.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Regional Council of Higher Education (ARCHE) is dedicated to strengthening synergy among 19 public and private colleges and universities in the Atlanta region.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Participating Atlanta region colleges and universities partner on joint-degree programs, cross-registration, library services, and cultural events.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Approximately 49,000 students are enrolled in 106 schools in Atlanta Public Schools (APS), some of which are operated as charter schools.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2018, the City of Atlanta annexed a portion of DeKalb County containing the Centers for Disease Control and Emory University; this portion was to be zoned to the DeKalb County School District until 2024, when it was to transition into APS.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2017 the number of children living in the annexed territory who attended public schools was nine.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The primary network-affiliated television stations in Atlanta are WSB-TV 2 (ABC), WAGA-TV 5 (Fox)., WXIA-TV 11 (NBC), WPXA-TV 14 (Ion), WPCH-TV 17, (CW), WUVG-TV 34 (Univision/UniMás), WATL 36 (MyNetworkTV), WANF 46 (Independent), WKTB-CD 47 (Telemundo) and WUPA 69 (CBS).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta metropolitan area is served by two public television stations (both PBS member stations) and two public radio stations.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] WGTV 8 is the flagship station of the statewide Georgia Public Television network, while WABE-TV 30 is owned by Atlanta Public Schools.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Georgia Public Radio is listener-funded and comprises one NPR member station, WABE, a classical music station also operated by Atlanta Public Schools.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The second public radio, listener-funded NPR member station is WCLK, a jazz music station owned and operated by Clark Atlanta University.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is served by *The Atlanta Journal-Constitution*, its only major daily newspaper with wide distribution (the *AJC* stopped publishing a physical newspaper in 2026 in favor of digital coverage).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The *Atlanta Journal-Constitution* is the result of a 1950 merger between *The Atlanta Journal* and *The Atlanta Constitution*, with staff consolidation occurring in 1982 and separate publication of the morning *Constitution* and afternoon *Journal* ceasing in 2001.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Alternative weekly newspapers include *Creative Loafing*, which has a weekly print circulation of 80,000.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] *Atlanta Daily World* is the oldest Black newspaper in Atlanta and one of the earliest Black newspapers in American history.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] *Atlanta* magazine is a monthly general-interest magazine based in and covering Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta has a network of freeways that radiate out from the city, and automobiles are the dominant means of transportation in the region.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Three major interstate highways converge in Atlanta: I-20 (east-west), I-75 (northwest-southeast), and I-85 (northeast-southwest).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The latter two combine in the middle of the city to form the Downtown Connector (I-75/85), which carries more than 340,000 vehicles per day and is one of the most congested segments of interstate highway in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta is mostly encircled by Interstate 285, a beltway locally known as "the Perimeter" that has come to mark the boundary between "Inside the Perimeter" (ITP), the city and close-in suburbs, and "Outside the Perimeter" (OTP), the outer suburbs and exurbs.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The heavy reliance on automobiles for transportation in Atlanta has resulted in traffic, commute, and air pollution rates that rank among the worst in the country.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The City of Atlanta has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2015, 15.2 percent of Atlanta households lacked a car, and this percentage increased slightly to 16.4 percent in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Atlanta averaged 1.31 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority (MARTA) provides public transportation in the form of buses, heavy rail, and a downtown light rail loop.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Notwithstanding heavy automotive usage in Atlanta, the city's subway system is the eighth busiest in the country.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] MARTA rail lines connect key destinations, such as the airport, Downtown, Midtown, Buckhead, and Perimeter Center.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] However, significant destinations, such as Emory University and Cumberland, remain unserved.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] As a result, a 2011 Brookings Institution study placed Atlanta 91st of 100 metro areas for transit accessibility.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Emory University operates its Cliff shuttle buses with 200,000 boardings per month, while private minibuses supply Buford Highway.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Amtrak, the national rail passenger system, provides service to Atlanta via the *Crescent train* (New York–New Orleans), which stops at Peachtree Station.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2014, the Atlanta Streetcar opened to the public.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The streetcar's line, which is also known as the Downtown Loop, runs 2.7 miles (4.3 km) around the downtown tourist areas of Peachtree Center, Centennial Olympic Park, the Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] National Historical Park, and Sweet Auburn.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The Atlanta Streetcar line is also being expanded on in the coming years to include a wider range of Atlanta's neighborhoods and important places of interest, with a total of over 50 miles (80 km) of track in the plan.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport is the world's busiest airport as measured by passenger traffic and aircraft traffic.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The facility offers air service to over 150 U.S. destinations and more than 75 international destinations in 50 countries, with over 2,500 arrivals and departures daily.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Delta Air Lines maintains its largest hub at the airport.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Situated 10 miles (16 km) south of downtown in Clayton and Fulton counties, the airport covers most of the land inside a wedge formed by Interstate 75, Interstate 85, and Interstate 285.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Cycling is a growing mode of transportation in Atlanta, more than doubling since 2009, when it comprised 1.1% of all commutes (up from 0.3% in 2000).
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Although Atlanta's lack of bike lanes and hilly topography may deter many residents from cycling, the city's transportation plan calls for the construction of 226 miles (364 km) of bike lanes by 2020, with the Beltline helping to achieve this goal.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] In 2012, Atlanta's first "bike track" was constructed on 10th Street in Midtown.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The two-lane bike track runs from Monroe Drive west to Charles Allen Drive, with connections to the Beltline and Piedmont Park.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] Starting in June 2016, Atlanta received a bike sharing program, known as Relay Bike Share, with 100 bikes in Downtown and Midtown, which expanded to 500 bikes at 65 stations as of April 2017.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] According to the 2016 American Community Survey (five-year average), 68.6% of working city of Atlanta residents commuted by driving alone, 7% carpooled, 10% used public transportation, and 4.6% walked.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] About 2.1% used all other forms of transportation, including taxi, bicycle, and motorcycle.
[src:howstuffworks/atlanta-p02] The city has also become one of a handful of "scooter capitals", where companies like Lime and Bird have gained a major foothold by placing electric scooters on street corners and byways.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans grew up in Idabel, Oklahoma and Plano, Texas, and graduated from Plano East Senior High School in 2006.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] His parents tried to open several small businesses and admired Ronald Reagan and Pat Buchanan.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans worked at the humor website *Cracked* as an editorial manager.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In that position, Evans led a team that published "personal experience" articles.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] These articles fell into two main categories: journalistic pieces involving a variety of sources and personal narratives.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In 2016 Evans published his first book, *A Brief History of Vice,* about the formative effects of narcotics on the development and history of civilization.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans has done reporting for the investigative reporting outlet Bellingcat between 2018 and 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] He has reported on conflicts in Iraq, Ukraine, and Rojava, as well as on far-right extremists in the United States.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Following the March 2019 Christchurch mosque shootings, news outlets including *Rolling Stone*, *Vox*, and *The Atlantic* referenced Evans' warning about the nature of the shooter's manifesto.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans argued that the manifesto was merely a red herring, full of references and memes meant to distract observers.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Following the 2019 Poway synagogue shooting, *Vox* relied on Evans' work to explain how the shooter's manifesto again constituted a 74-page in-joke meant to further radicalize other 4chan /pol/ users.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In a 2020 Bellingcat article, Evans discussed the emergence and qualities of the boogaloo movement, a loose-knit group of individuals who express interest in fomenting American civil unrest.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans says that he became aware of the boogaloo movement when he observed members at 2020 Virginia Citizens Defence League Lobby Day.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Starting in late May 2020, Evans covered the George Floyd protests in Portland, Oregon.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] He began reporting in the first days of the protests by taking footage of protesters, counter-protesters, and police.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] His reporting on the protests was highlighted in the *New York Times* opinion section, which published an interview with Evans after the 50th day of protests about covering the events.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In July, Evans joined a class-action lawsuit against the City of Portland for police use of force at the protests.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] The suit alleges that police officers were unlawfully violent, stopped journalists from reporting, and interfered with the right to free speech.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] The suit describes incidents that occurred to Evans including the "police allegedly threatening him with arrest if he did not leave the area, shooting him in the foot with a tear gas grenade and spraying him, and repeatedly shoving him".
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] On Saturday, August 22, a right-wing protester wielding a baton broke Evans' hand while he was filming.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In an interview with *The Guardian*, Evans said the right-wing counter-protesters "absolutely came prepared to fight", were "very aggressive from the jump", and were equipped with "knives, guns, paintball guns with frozen pellets, batons".
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans is the host of the podcast *Behind the Bastards* and one of three co-hosts of the podcast *Worst Year Ever*.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In 2019, Evans completed the podcast series *The War on Everyone*, a podcast about how white supremacy and fascism have developed and spread into the American consciousness in the modern age, as well as *It Could Happen Here*, a podcast about the possibility of a Second American Civil War.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans published a new podcast series titled *The Women's War* in March and April 2020 about the primarily Kurdish autonomous region in Syria known as Rojava.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Evans also published a *Behind the Bastards* podcast miniseries titled *Behind the Police* in June and July 2020, covering the history of policing in the United States to inform the present time of civil unrest.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] Behind the Police was co-hosted by Jason "Propaganda" Petty.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In November 2020 through early 2021, Evans published *Uprising: A Guide From Portland*, a podcast detailing first-hand accounts of the 2020 George Floyd protests in Portland, Oregon.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] After a deal between iHeartMedia and Netflix was signed in December 2025, *Behind the Bastards* began streaming on Netflix in January 2026.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] In August 2021, iHeartMedia announced a launch of a new podcast network Cool Zone Media helmed by Evans, who would become its head of content.
[src:howstuffworks/behind-the-bastards] The network would unite under one umbrella both existing and upcoming podcasts from Evans and his frequent collaborators such as Jake Hanrahan and Petty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing is a global city and one of the world's leading centers for culture, diplomacy, politics, finance, business and economics, education, research, language, tourism, media, sports, science and technology, transportation, and art.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] It is home to the headquarters of most of China's largest state-owned companies and houses the largest number of *Fortune* Global 500 companies in the world, as well as the world's four biggest financial institutions by total assets.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] It is also a major hub for the national highway, expressway, railway, and high-speed rail networks.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] For a decade before the COVID-19 pandemic, Beijing Capital International Airport was Asia's busiest airport (2009–2019) and the second-busiest airport in the world (2010–2019).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2020, the Beijing subway was the fourth-busiest and second-longest in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing Daxing International Airport, Beijing's second international airport, is the largest single-structure airport terminal in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city has hosted numerous international and national sporting events, the most notable being the 2008 Summer Olympics and 2008 Summer Paralympics Games.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2022, Beijing became the first city ever to host both the Summer and Winter Olympics, and also the Summer and Winter Paralympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The architecture of Beijing contains elements of both traditional Chinese architecture with modern styles, with one side of the city being modernized and renovated, and the other half still offering traditional *hutong* districts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing is one of the oldest cities in the world, with recorded history spanning over three millennia.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] As the last remaining one of the Four Great Ancient Capitals of China, Beijing has been the political center of the country for most of the past eight centuries, and was the largest city in the world by population for much of the second millennium AD.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] With mountains surrounding the inland city on three sides, in addition to the ancient city fortifications, Beijing was strategically poised and developed to be the residence of the emperor.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city is renowned for its opulent palaces, temples, parks, gardens, tombs, walls and gates.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing is considered one of the most well-known tourist destinations in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2018, Beijing was the second highest earning tourist city in the world after Shanghai.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Siheyuans, the city's traditional housing style, and hutongs, the narrow alleys between siheyuans, are major tourist attractions and are common in urban Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing's public universities make up more than one-fifth of Double First-Class Construction universities, and many of them consistently rank among the best in the Asia-Pacific and the world, including Tsinghua University, Peking University and UCAS.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing CBD is a center for Beijing's economic expansion, with the ongoing or recently completed construction of multiple skyscrapers.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing's Zhongguancun area is a world leading center of scientific and technological innovation as well as entrepreneurship.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing has been ranked the city with the largest scientific research output by the Nature Index since the list's inception in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Over the past 3,000 years, the city of Beijing has had numerous other names.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The name *Beijing*, which means 'Northern Capital' (from the Chinese characters 北 *běi* for 'north' and 京 *jīng* for 'capital'), was applied to the city in 1403 during the Ming dynasty to distinguish the city from Nanjing (南京, 'Southern Capital').
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The English spelling *Beijing* is based on the government's official romanization (adopted in the 1980s) of the two characters as they are pronounced in Standard Mandarin.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] An older English spelling, *Peking*, was used by Jesuit missionary Martino Martini in a popular atlas published in Amsterdam in 1655.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Although Peking is no longer the common name for the city, some of the city's older locations and facilities, such as Beijing Capital International Airport, with the IATA code PEK, and Peking University, still retain the former romanization.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The single Chinese character abbreviation for Beijing is 京, which appears on automobile license plates in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The official Latin alphabet abbreviation for Beijing is "BJ".
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The earliest traces of human habitation in the Beijing municipality were found in the caves of Dragon Bone Hill near the village of Zhoukoudian in Fangshan District, where Peking Man lived.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] *Homo erectus* fossils from the caves date to 230,000 to 250,000 years ago.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Paleolithic *Homo sapiens* also lived there more recently, about 27,000 years ago.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Archaeologists have found neolithic settlements throughout the municipality, including in Wangfujing, located in central Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The first walled city in Beijing was Ji, the eponymous capital city of the state of Ji.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Within modern Beijing, Ji was located around the present Guang'anmen area in the south of Xicheng District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the early Zhou period, this settlement was conquered by the state of Yan (11th century BC – 222 BC), whose original capital was located 45 kilometres (28 mi) southwest in Fangshan District, and made its new capital.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Yan eventually became one of the seven major states of China during the Warring States period (c.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] After the First Emperor unified China in 221 BC, Ji became the capital of Guangyang Commandery.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the Han dynasty (202 BC – 220 AD), the city was first the capital of the subordinate Kingdom of Yan, and later again the seat of Guangyang Commandery after the kingdom was abolished.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Han divided the empire into 13 provinces, with Ji being the capital of You Province.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the Three Kingdoms period, it was held by Gongsun Zan and Yuan Shao before falling to Cao Cao.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The AD third-century Western Jin demoted the town, placing the prefectural seat in neighboring Zhuozhou.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the Sixteen Kingdoms period when northern China was conquered and divided by the Wu Hu, Ji was briefly the capital of the Xianbei Former Yan Kingdom.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] After China was reunified by the Sui dynasty in 581, Ji, as the seat of Zhuo Commandery, became the northern terminus of the Grand Canal.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Under the Tang dynasty, Ji as the center of You Prefecture (Youzhou), served as a military frontier command center.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the An-Shi Rebellion and again amidst the turmoil of the mid-Tang period, the rebel commander An Lushan founded the short-lived Yan dynasty and called the city Yanjing, or the "Yan Capital".
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Also in the Tang dynasty, the city's name Ji was replaced by Youzhou or Yanjing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Some of the oldest surviving pagodas in Beijing date to the Liao period, including the Tianning Pagoda.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Liao fell to the Jurchen Jin dynasty in 1122, which gave the city to the Song dynasty and then retook it in 1125 during its conquest of northern China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 1153, the Jurchen Jin made Beijing their "Central Capital", or Zhongdu.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city was besieged by Genghis Khan's invading Mongolian army in 1213 and razed to the ground two years later.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Two generations later, Kublai Khan ordered the construction of Dadu (or Daidu to the Mongols, commonly known as Khanbaliq), a new capital for his Yuan dynasty to the northeast of the Zhongdu ruins.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The construction took from 1264 to 1293, but greatly enhanced the status of a city on the northern fringe of China proper.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city was centered on the Drum Tower slightly to the north of modern Beijing and stretched from the present-day Chang'an Avenue to the northern part of Line 10 subway.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Remnants of the Yuan rammed earth wall still stand and are known as the Tucheng.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 1368, soon after declaring the new Hongwu era of the Ming dynasty, the rebel leader Zhu Yuanzhang captured Dadu/Khanbaliq and razed the Yuan palaces to the ground.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since the Yuan continued to occupy Shangdu and Mongolia, Dadu was used to supply the Ming military garrisons in the area and renamed Beiping (Wade–Giles: Peip'ing, "Northern Peace").
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Under the Hongwu Emperor's feudal policies, Beiping was given to his son Zhu Di, who was created "Prince of Yan".
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The early death of Zhu Yuanzhang's heir led to a succession struggle upon his death, one that ended with the victory of Zhu Di and the declaration of the new Yongle era.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since his harsh treatment of the Ming capital Yingtian (modern Nanjing) alienated many there, he established his fief as a new co-capital.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city of Beiping became Beijing ("Northern Capital") or Shuntian in 1403.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The construction of the new imperial residence, the Forbidden City, took from 1406 to 1420; this period was also responsible for several other of the modern city's major attractions, such as the Temple of Heaven and Tian'anmen.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On 28 October 1420, the city was officially designated the capital of the Ming dynasty in the same year that the Forbidden City was completed.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing became the empire's primary capital, and Yingtian, also called Nanjing ("Southern Capital"), became the co-capital.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] (A 1425 order by Zhu Di's son, the Hongxi Emperor, to return the primary capital to Nanjing was never carried out: he died, probably of a heart attack, the next month.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] By the 15th century, Beijing had essentially taken its current shape.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Ming city wall continued to serve until 1965, when it was pulled down and the Beijing Subway was built on its foundations.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] It is generally believed that Beijing was the largest city in the world for most of the 15th, 16th, 17th, and 18th centuries.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The first known church was constructed by Catholics in 1652 at the former site of Matteo Ricci's chapel; the modern Nantang Cathedral was later built upon the same site.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The capture of Beijing by Li Zicheng's peasant army in 1644 ended the dynasty, but he and his Shun court abandoned the city without a fight when the Manchu army of Prince Dorgon of the Qing dynasty arrived 40 days later.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing was declared the sole capital of the empire in 1644.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Qing emperors made some modifications to the Imperial residence but, in large part, the Ming buildings and the general layout remained unchanged.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Facilities for Manchu worship were introduced, but the Qing also continued the traditional state rituals.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] This early Qing Beijing later formed the setting for the Chinese novel *Dream of the Red Chamber*.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Northwest of the city, Qing emperors built several large palatial gardens including the Old Summer Palace and the Summer Palace.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the Second Opium War, Anglo-French forces captured the outskirts of the city, looting and burning the Old Summer Palace in 1860.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Under the Convention of Peking ending that war, Western powers for the first time secured the right to establish permanent diplomatic presences within the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] From 14 to 15 August 1900 the Battle of Peking was fought.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] This battle was part of the Boxer Rebellion.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The attempt by the Boxers to eradicate this presence, as well as Chinese Christian converts, led to Beijing's reoccupation by eight foreign powers.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the fighting, several important structures were destroyed, including the Hanlin Academy and the (new) Summer Palace.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] A peace agreement was concluded between the Eight-Nation Alliance and representatives of the Chinese government Li Hongzhang and Yikuang on 7 September 1901.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The treaty required China to pay an indemnity of US$335 million (over US$4 billion in current dollars) plus interest over a period of 39 years.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Also required was the execution or exile of government supporters of the Boxers and the destruction of Chinese forts and other defenses in much of northern China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Ten days after the treaty was signed the foreign armies left Beijing, although legation guards would remain there until World War II.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Dowager died in 1908 and the dynasty imploded in 1911.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The fomenters of the Xinhai Revolution of 1911 sought to replace Qing rule with a republic and leaders like Sun Yat-sen originally intended to return the capital to Nanjing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] After the Qing general Yuan Shikai forced the abdication of the last Qing emperor and ensured the success of the revolution, the revolutionaries accepted him as president of the new Republic of China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Yuan maintained his capital at Beijing and quickly consolidated power, declaring himself emperor in 1915.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] His death less than a year later left China under the control of the warlords commanding the regional armies.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Following the success of the Kuomintang's Northern Expedition, the capital was formally moved to Nanjing in 1928.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On 28 June the same year, Beijing's name was returned to Beiping (written at the time as "Peiping").
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On 7 July 1937, the 29th Army and the Japanese army in China exchanged fire at the Marco Polo Bridge near the Wanping Fortress southwest of the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Marco Polo Bridge Incident triggered the Second Sino-Japanese War, World War II as it is known in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the war, Beijing fell to Japan on 29 July 1937 and was made the seat of the Provisional Government of the Republic of China, a puppet state that ruled the ethnic-Chinese portions of Japanese-occupied northern China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] This government was later merged into the larger Wang Jingwei government based in Nanjing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In the final phases of the Chinese Civil War, the People's Liberation Army seized control of the city peacefully on 31 January 1949 in the course of the Pingjin Campaign.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On 1 October that year, Mao Zedong announced the creation of the People's Republic of China from atop Tiananmen.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] He restored the name of the city, as the new capital, to Beijing, a decision that had been reached by the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference just a few days earlier.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In the 1950s, the city began to expand beyond the old walled city and its surrounding neighborhoods, with heavy industries in the west and residential neighborhoods in the north.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Many areas of the Beijing city wall were torn down in the 1960s to make way for the construction of the Beijing Subway and the 2nd Ring Road.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During the Cultural Revolution from 1966 to 1976, the Red Guard movement began in Beijing and the city's government fell victim to one of the first purges.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] By the autumn of 1966, all city schools were shut down and over a million Red Guards from across the country gathered in Beijing for eight rallies in Tiananmen Square with Mao.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In April 1976, a large public gathering of Beijing residents in Tiananmen Square, protesting against the Gang of Four and the Cultural Revolution, was forcefully suppressed.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In October 1976, the Gang was arrested in Zhongnanhai and the Cultural Revolution came to an end.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In December 1978, the Third Plenum of the 11th Party Congress in Beijing under the leadership of Deng Xiaoping reversed the verdicts against victims of the Cultural Revolution and instituted the reform and opening up.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since the early 1980s, the urban area of Beijing has expanded greatly with the completion of the 2nd Ring Road in 1981 and the subsequent addition of the 3rd, 4th, 5th and 6th ring roads.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] According to one 2005 newspaper report, the newly developed Beijing was one-and-a-half times its previous size.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Wangfujing and Xidan have developed into flourishing shopping districts, while Zhongguancun has become a major center of electronics in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In recent years, the expansion of Beijing has also brought to the forefront some problems of urbanization, such as heavy traffic, poor air quality, the loss of historic neighborhoods, and a significant influx of migrant workers from less-developed rural areas of the country.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city has also been the location of many significant events in recent Chinese history, principally the Tiananmen Square protests of 1989.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing has hosted major international sporting events, including the 2008 Summer Olympics, the 2015 World Athletics Championships, and the 2022 Winter Olympics, and is the only city to have hosted both the Winter and Summer Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In terms of international connectedness, as of 2024, Beijing was one of eight cities worldwide that was classified as an "Alpha+" city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Three styles of architecture are predominant in urban Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] First, there is the traditional architecture of imperial China, perhaps best exemplified by the massive Tian'anmen (Gate of Heavenly Peace), which remains the People's Republic of China's trademark edifice, the Forbidden City, the Imperial Ancestral Temple and the Temple of Heaven.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Next, there is what is sometimes referred to as the "Sino-Sov" style, with structures tending to be boxy and sometimes poorly constructed, which were built between the 1950s and the 1970s.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Finally, there are much more modern architectural forms, most noticeably in the area of the Beijing CBD in east Beijing such as the new CCTV Headquarters, in addition to buildings in other locations around the city such as the Beijing National Stadium and National Center for the Performing Arts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In the early 21st century, Beijing has witnessed tremendous growth of new building constructions, exhibiting various modern styles from international designers, most pronounced in the CBD region.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] A mixture of both 1950s design and neofuturistic style of architecture can be seen at the 798 Art Zone, which mixes the old with the new.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing's tallest building is the 528-meter China Zun.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since 2007, buildings in Beijing have received the CTBUH Skyscraper Award for best overall tall building twice, for the Linked Hybrid building in 2009 and the CCTV Headquarters in 2013.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The CTBUH Skyscraper award for best tall overall building is given to only one building around the world every year.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing is situated at the northern edge of the roughly triangular North China Plain, which opens to the south and east of the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Mountains to the north, northwest and west shield the city and northern China's agricultural heartland from the encroaching desert steppes.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The northwestern part of the municipality, especially Yanqing District and Huairou District, are dominated by the Jundu Mountains, while the western part is framed by *Xishan* or the Western Hills.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Great Wall of China across the northern part of Beijing Municipality was built on the rugged topography to defend against nomadic incursions from the steppes.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Mount Dongling, in the Western Hills and on the border with Hebei, is the municipality's highest point, with an altitude of 2,303 metres (7,556 ft).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Major rivers flowing through the municipality, including the Chaobai, Yongding, Juma, are all tributaries in the Hai River system, and flow in a southeasterly direction.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Miyun Reservoir, on the upper reaches of the Chaobai River, is the largest reservoir within the municipality.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing is also the northern terminus of the Grand Canal to Hangzhou, which was built over 1,400 years ago as a transportation route, and the South–North Water Transfer Project, constructed in the past decade to bring water from the Yangtze River basin.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The urban area of Beijing, on the plains in the south-central of the municipality with elevation of 40 to 60 metres (130–200 feet), occupies a relatively small but expanding portion of the municipality's area.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city spreads out in concentric ring roads.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The Second Ring Road traces the old city walls and the Sixth Ring Road connects satellite towns in the surrounding suburbs.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Tian'anmen and Tian'anmen Square are at the center of Beijing, directly to the south of the Forbidden City, the former residence of the emperors of China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] To the west of Tian'anmen is Zhongnanhai, the residence of China's current leaders.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Chang'an Avenue, which cuts between Tiananmen and the Square, forms the city's main east–west axis.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing's pattern of development from the old inner city to its urban fringe are frequently described as "spreading like a pancake" (*tan da bing*).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] This pattern of development is frequently cited as a reason for Beijing's urban problems.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing has a humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dwa*), bordering on a monsoonal cold semi-arid climate (Köppen: *BSk*).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city is characterized by hot, humid summers due to the East Asian monsoon as well as brief but cold, dry winters that reflect the influence of the vast Siberian anticyclone.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Spring can bear witness to sandstorms blowing in from the Gobi Desert across the Mongolian steppe, accompanied by rapidly warming, but generally dry, conditions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Autumn, similar to spring, is a season of transition and minimal precipitation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] From 2001 to 2024, the hottest period in Beijing is early August, and the coldest period is late January.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] According to China's seasonal division standard, Beijing enters spring on 26 March, summer on 20 May, autumn on 13 September, and winter on 31 October.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Due to the faster warming in March and September and the slower warming in May and October in recent years, Beijing is generally shorter in autumn than in spring.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The average annual temperature in the urban area of Beijing is 12.9 °C (55.2 °F) to 13.3 °C (55.9 °F), of which the average daily minimum temperature is 7.7 °C (45.9 °F) to 8.4 °C (47.1 °F), and the average daily maximum temperature is 18.5 °C (65.3 °F) to 18.9 °C (66.0 °F).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The monthly daily average temperature in January is −2.7 °C (27.1 °F), while in July it is 27.2 °C (81.0 °F).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Precipitation averages around 528.0 mm (20.79 in) annually (Haidian and Chaoyang has an average annual precipitation of 584.2 mm (23.00 in)), with close to three-quarters of that total falling from June to August.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 42% in July to 62% in January and February, the city receives 2,490.5 hours of bright sunshine annually.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] When Europeans first came into sustained contact with China, "Pekin" and "Peking" were the most popular ways of romanizing the name of Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing had a long history of environmental problems.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Between 2000 and 2009 Beijing's urban extent quadrupled, which not only strongly increased the extent of anthropogenic emissions, but also changed the meteorological situation fundamentally, even if emissions of human society are not included.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] For example, surface albedo, wind speed and humidity near the surface were decreased, whereas ground and near-surface air temperatures, vertical air dilution and ozone levels were increased.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Because of the combined factors of urbanization and pollution caused by burning of fossil fuel, Beijing is often affected by serious environmental problems, which lead to health issues of many inhabitants.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2013 heavy smog struck Beijing and most parts of northern China, impacting a total of 600 million people.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] After this "pollution shock" air pollution became an important economic and social concern in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Joint research between American and Chinese researchers in 2006 concluded that much of the city's pollution comes from surrounding cities and provinces.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On average 35–60% of the ozone can be traced to sources outside the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Shandong Province and Tianjin Municipality have a "significant influence on Beijing's air quality", partly due to the prevailing south/southeasterly flow during the summer and the mountains to the north and northwest.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In preparation for the 2008 Summer Olympics and to fulfill promises to clean up the city's air, nearly US$17 billion was spent.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The city further assembled 3,800 natural gas-powered buses, one of the largest fleets in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing became the first city in China to require the Chinese equivalent to the Euro 4 emission standard.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Coal burning accounts for about 40% of the PM 2.5 in Beijing and is also the chief source of nitrogen and sulphur dioxide.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since 2012, the city has been converting coal-fired power stations to burn natural gas and aims to cap annual coal consumption at 20 million tons.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2011, the city burned 26.3 million tons of coal, 73% of which for heating and power generation and the remainder for industry.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Much of the city's air pollutants are emitted by neighboring regions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Coal consumption in neighboring Tianjin is expected to increase from 48 to 63 million tons from 2011 to 2015.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Hebei Province burned over 300 million tons of coal in 2011, more than all of Germany, of which only 30% were used for power generation and a considerable portion for steel and cement making.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Power plants in the coal-mining regions of Shanxi, Inner Mongolia and Shaanxi, where coal consumption has tripled since 2000, and Shandong also contribute to air pollution in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Shandong, Shanxi, Hebei and Inner Mongolia, respectively rank from first to fourth, among Chinese provinces by coal consumption.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] There were four major coal-fired power plants in the city to provide electricity as well as heating during the winter.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The first one (Gaojing Thermal Power Plant) was shut down in 2014.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The last one (Huaneng Thermal Power Plant) would be shut in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Between 2013 and 2017, the city planned to reduce 13 million tons of coal consumption and cap coal consumption to 15 million tons in 2015.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The government sometimes uses cloud-seeding measures to increase the likelihood of rain showers in the region to clear the air prior to large events, such as prior to the 60th anniversary parade in 2009 as well as to combat drought conditions in the area.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] During and prior to these events, Beijing's air quality improved dramatically, only to fall back to unhealthy levels shortly after.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] On 8 and 9 December 2015 Beijing had its first smog alert which shut down a majority of the industry and other commercial businesses in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Later in the month another smog "red alert" was issued.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] According to Beijing's environmental protection bureau's announcement in November 2016, starting from 2017 highly polluting old cars will be banned from being driven whenever Smog "red alerts" are issued in the city or neighboring regions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In recent years, there has been measurable reductions in pollutants after the "war on pollution" was declared in 2014, with Beijing seeing a 35% reduction in fine particulates in 2017 and further reduction by 2020.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The primary factors behind this reduction were replacing coal power with natural gas and cleaning up polluting industrial facilities in the Beijing area.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Beijing's annual average concentration of major airborne fine particulate matter, or PM2.5, declined to 30 micrograms per cubic meter in 2022, the best air quality for the city since 2013.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In 2024, Beijing experienced only two days of heavy pollution, the lowest number on record, which had decreased by 96.6 percent from 58 days in 2013.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Due to Beijing's high level of air pollution, there are various readings by different sources on the subject.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Daily pollution readings at 27 monitoring stations around the city are reported on the website of the Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau (BJEPB).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The American Embassy of Beijing also reports hourly fine particulate (PM2.5) and ozone levels on Twitter.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Since the BJEPB and US Embassy measure different pollutants according to different criteria, the pollution levels and the impact to human health reported by the BJEPB are often lower than that reported by the US Embassy.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The smog is causing harm and danger to the population.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] The air pollution does directly result in significant impact on the morbidity rate of cardiovascular disease and respiratory disease in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Exposure to large concentrations of polluted air can cause respiratory and cardiovascular problems, emergency room visits, and even death.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] Dust from the erosion of deserts in northern and northwestern China results in seasonal dust storms that plague the city; the Beijing Weather Modification Office sometimes artificially induces rainfall to fight such storms and mitigate their effects.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In the first four months of 2006 alone, there were no fewer than eight such storms.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p01] In April 2002, one dust storm alone dumped nearly 50,000 tons of dust onto the city before moving on to Japan and Korea.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The municipal government is regulated by the Municipal Committee of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP), led by the Beijing CCP Secretary.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Municipal CCP Committee issues administrative orders, collects taxes, manages the economy, and directs a standing committee of the Municipal People's Congress in making policy decisions and overseeing the local government.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Since 1987, all CCP Secretary of Beijing is also a member of the Politburo.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Government officials include the mayor (Chinese: 市长) and vice-mayor.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Numerous bureaus focus on law, public security, and other affairs.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Additionally, as the capital of China, Beijing houses all of the important national governmental and political institutions, including the National People's Congress.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Municipality currently comprises 16 administrative county-level subdivisions, namely 16 urban districts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] On 1 July 2010, Chongwen and Xuanwu were merged into Dongcheng and Xicheng, respectively.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] On 13 November 2015 Miyun and Yanqing were upgraded to districts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing's 16 county-level divisions (districts) are further subdivided into 273 lower third-level administrative units at the township level: 119 towns, 24 townships, 5 ethnic townships and 125 subdistricts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Several place names in Beijing end with *mén* (门), meaning "gate", as they were the locations of gates in the former Beijing city wall.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Other place names end in *cūn* (村), meaning "village", as they were originally villages outside the city wall.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 1 Intermediate People's Court in Shijingshan oversees the basic courts of Haidian, Shijingshan, Mentougou, Changping and Yanqing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 2 Intermediate People's Court in Fengtai oversees the basic courts of Dongcheng, Xicheng, Fengtai, Fangshan and Daxing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 3 Intermediate People's Court in Laiguangying, is the newest of the three intermediate people's courts and opened on 21 August 2013.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] It oversees the district courts of Chaoyang, Tongzhou, Shunyi, Huairou, Pinggu and Miyun.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Each court in Beijing has a corresponding people's procuratorate.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As of 2025, Beijing's GDP was CN¥5.2 trillion ($748 billion in nominal, $1.52 trillion in PPP), about 3.71% of the country's GDP and ranked 12th among province-level administrative units; its GDP per capita was CN¥238,571 (US$34,252 in norminal; US$69,962 in PPP) and ranked the 1st in the country.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] It also ranks the tenth largest in the metropolitan economies in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Due to the concentration of state owned enterprises in the national capital, Beijing in 2013 had more Fortune Global 500 Company headquarters than any other city in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As of August 2022, Beijing has 54 Fortune Global 500 companies, more than Japan (47), the third-place country after China (145) and the United States (124).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing has also been described as the "billionaire capital of the world".
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing is classified as an Alpha+ (global first-tier) city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, indicating its influence in the region and worldwide and making it one of the world's Top 10 major cities.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In the 2021 Global Financial Centres Index, Beijing was ranked as having the sixth-most competitive financial center in the world and fourth-most competitive in the whole Asia & Oceania region (behind Shanghai, Hong Kong and Singapore).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As of 2021, Beijing was ranked first globally in terms of "*Global City Competitiveness*" in the *2020–2021 Global Urban Competitiveness Report* jointly released by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) and the United Nations Programme for Human Settlements (UN-Habitat).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The city has a post-industrial economy that is dominated by the tertiary sector (services), which generated 83.8% of output, followed by the secondary sector (manufacturing, construction) at 15.8% and the primary sector (agriculture, mining) at 0.26%.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The services sector is broadly diversified with professional services, wholesale and retail, information technology, commercial real estate, scientific research, and residential real estate each contributing at least 6% to the city's economy in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The single largest sub-sector remains industry, whose share of overall output has shrunk to 12.1% in 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The mix of industrial output has changed significantly since 2010 when the city announced that 140 highly-polluting, energy and water resource intensive enterprises would be relocated from the city in five years.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The relocation of Capital Steel to neighboring Hebei province had begun in 2005.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2013, output of automobiles, aerospace products, semiconductors, pharmaceuticals, and food processing all increased.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In the farmland around Beijing, vegetables and fruits have displaced grain as the primary crops under cultivation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2013, the tonnage of vegetable, edible fungus and fruit harvested was over three times that of grain.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2013, overall acreage under cultivation shrank along with most categories of produce as more land was reforested for environmental reasons.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2006, the city government identified six high-end economic output zones around Beijing as the primary engines for local economic growth.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2012, the six zones produced 43.3% of the city's GDP, up from 36.5% in 2007.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Financial Street, in Xicheng District on the west side of the city between Fuxingmen and Fuchengmen, is lined with headquarters of large state banks and insurance companies.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The country's financial regulatory agencies including the central bank, bank regulator, securities regulator, and foreign exchange authority are located in the neighborhood.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Central Business District (CBD), is actually located to the east of downtown, near the embassies along the eastern Third Ring Road between Jianguomenwai and Chaoyangmenwai.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The CBD is home to most of the city's skyscraper office buildings.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Most of the city's foreign companies and professional service firms are based in the CBD.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Economic and Technological Development Area, better known as Yizhuang, is an industrial park the straddles the southern Fifth Ring Road in Daxing District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] It has attracted pharmaceutical, information technology, and materials engineering companies.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Airport Economic Zone was created in 1993 and surrounds the Beijing Capital International Airport in Shunyi District northeast of the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In addition to logistics, airline services, and trading firms, this zone is also home to Beijing's automobile assembly plants.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Olympic Center Zone surrounds the Olympic Green due north of downtown and is developing into an entertainment, sports, tourism and business convention center.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Shijingshan, on the western outskirts of the city, was a traditional heavy industrial base of the steel-maker Shougang Group.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] After production ceased in 2010, the site was transformed into a center for industrial culture, fairs, art exhibits and sports events, including a venue for the 2022 Winter Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] A former chemical industrial park in the far eastern suburbs has been converted into a forest park.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2024, Beijing had a total population of 21.83 million within the municipality, of which 19.26 million (88.2 percent) resided in urban districts or suburban townships and 2.57 million (11.8) lived in rural villages.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The encompassing metropolitan area was estimated by the OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development) to have, as of 2010, a population of 24.9 million.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Within China, the city ranked second in urban population after Shanghai and the third in municipal population after Shanghai and Chongqing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing also ranks among the most populous cities in the world, a distinction the city has held for much of the past 800 years, especially during the 15th to early 19th centuries when it was the largest city in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] About 13 million of the city's residents in 2013 had local *hukou* permits, which entitles them to permanent residence in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The remaining 8 million residents had *hukou* permits elsewhere and were not eligible to receive some social benefits provided by the Beijing municipal government.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The population increased in 2013 by 455,000 or about 7% from the previous year and continued a decade-long trend of rapid growth.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The total population in 2004 was 14.213 million.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The population gains are driven largely by migration.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The population's rate of natural increase in 2013 was a mere 0.441%, based on a birth rate of 8.93 and a mortality rate of 4.52.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The gender balance was 51.6% males and 48.4% females.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Working age people account for nearly 73.6% of the population.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Compared to 2004, residents age 0–14 as a proportion of the population dropped from 9.95% to 9.92% in 2013, but again increased to 12.1% in 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Residents over the age of 65 declined from 11.12% to 8.58%, but increased to 14.2% in 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of city residents with at least some college education nearly doubled, from 20.4% to 37.3%, and further increased to 49.1% by 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] About 66.4% have senior secondary school education and 88.2% had reached middle school.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 96% of Beijing's population are ethnic Han Chinese.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In addition, there were 8,045 Hong Kong residents, 500 Macau residents, and 7,772 Taiwan residents along with 91,128 registered foreigners living in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] A study by the Beijing Academy of Sciences estimates that in 2010 there were on average 200,000 foreigners living in Beijing on any given day including students, business travellers and tourists that are not counted as registered residents.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2017 the Chinese government implemented population controls for Beijing and Shanghai to fight what it called the "big city disease" which includes congestion, pollution, and shortages of education and health care services.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] From this policy, Beijing's population declined by 20,000 from 2016 to 2017.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Some low-income people are being forcibly removed from the city as both legal and illegal housing is being demolished in some high-density residential neighborhoods.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The population is being redistributed to Jing-Jin-Ji and Xiong'an New Area, the transfer to the latter expected to include 300,000-500,000 people working in government research, universities, and corporate headquarters.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing is a world-leading center for scientific and technological innovation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 1 city in the world with the largest scientific research output, as tracked by the Nature Index since the list's inception in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] When compared to countries, Beijing ranked above Germany, securing third place worldwide after China and the US, according to the Nature Index for 2025.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] For example, Beijing's share of the 2024 Nature Index is 5,501.45 with 11,915 counts, while Germany's share is 5,000.90 with 10,559 counts.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The capital also leads the world with the highest share of articles published in chemistry, physical sciences, Earth & environmental sciences, and natural sciences, especially in the United Nations 17 Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)-related output.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As of 2024, it stands as the most prolific scientific research center in biological sciences and health science in the Asia-Pacific, ranking third and sixth in the world, respectively.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing has over 90 public colleges and universities, making it the largest urban public university system in Asia and the first city in China with the most higher education institutions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] It is also home to the two best universities (Tsinghua and Peking) in the whole of the Asia & Oceania region and emerging countries, with their rankings at #12 and #13 places in the world, respectively by the 2025 Times Higher Education World University Rankings.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Both are members of the C9 League, an alliance of elite Chinese universities offering comprehensive and leading education.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing represents more than one-fifth of 147 Double First-Class Universities, a national plan to develop elite Chinese universities into world-class institutions by the end of 2050.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] News & World Report Best Global University Ranking for 2026–2027, Beijing has the highest number of universities among major cities in the world included in the ranking, totaling 31, with 2 universities in the top 20, 7 institutions in the top 200 and 12 institutions in the top 500.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to the Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU) for 2025, Beijing has 2 universities in the top 25, 7 institutions in the top 200, and 13 institutions in the top 500.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] These universities were selected as "985 universities" or "211 universities" by the Chinese government in order to build world-class universities.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The city is a seat of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, which has been consistently ranked the No.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 1 research institute in the world by *Nature Index* since the list's inception in 2014.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The academy also runs the University of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, which is located in Beijing and ranked among the world's top five research institutions by the Nature Index.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] People native to urban Beijing speak the Beijing dialect, which belongs to the Mandarin subdivision of spoken Chinese.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] This speech is the basis for *putonghua*, the standard spoken language used in mainland China and Taiwan, and one of the four official languages of Singapore.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Rural areas of Beijing Municipality have their own dialects akin to those of Hebei province, which surrounds Beijing Municipality.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Younger residents of Beijing have become more attracted to the nightlife, which has flourished in recent decades, breaking prior cultural traditions that had practically restricted it to the upper class.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Today, Houhai, Sanlitun and Wudaokou are Beijing's nightlife hotspots.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing or Peking opera is a traditional form of Chinese theater well known throughout the nation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Commonly lauded as one of the highest achievements of Chinese culture, Beijing opera is performed through a combination of song, spoken dialogue, and codified action sequences involving gestures, movement, fighting and acrobatics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Much of Beijing opera is carried out in an archaic stage dialect quite different from Modern Standard Chinese and from the modern Beijing dialect.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The cloisonné (or *Jingtailan*, literally "Blue of Jingtai") metalworking technique and tradition is a Beijing art speciality, and is one of the most revered traditional crafts in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Cloisonné making requires elaborate and complicated processes which include base-hammering, copper-strip inlay, soldering, enamel-filling, enamel-firing, surface polishing and gilding.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing's lacquerware is also well known for its sophisticated and intricate patterns and images carved into its surface, and the various decoration techniques of lacquer include "carved lacquer" and "engraved gold".
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2012 Beijing was named as City of Design and became part of the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing cuisine has been shaped by centuries of imperial court cooking, the culinary traditions of surrounding regions, and the influence of ethnic minorities including Manchu and Mongol peoples.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As the imperial capital for over 500 years, Beijing attracted cooks and ingredients from across China, giving rise to a distinctive style that blends northern Chinese staples with court refinement.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Peking duck is perhaps the best known dish.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Fuling jiabing, a traditional Beijing snack food, is a pancake (*bing*) resembling a flat disk with a filling made from *fu ling*, a fungus used in traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Instant-boiled mutton, served in a traditional copper hot pot, is another iconic Beijing dish with origins dating to the Yuan dynasty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] At the historical heart of Beijing lies the Forbidden City, the enormous palace compound that was the home of the emperors of the Ming and Qing dynasties; the Forbidden City hosts the Palace Museum, which contains imperial collections of Chinese art.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Surrounding the Forbidden City are several former imperial gardens, parks and scenic areas, notably Beihai, Shichahai, Jingshan and Zhongshan Park.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] From Tiananmen Square, right across from the Forbidden City, there are several notable sites, such as the Tian'anmen, Qianmen, the Great Hall of the People, the National Museum of China, the Monument to the People's Heroes, and the Mausoleum of Mao Zedong.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Summer Palace and the Old Summer Palace both lie at the western part of the city; the former, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, contains a comprehensive collection of imperial gardens and palaces that served as the summer retreats for the Qing imperial family.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Among the best known religious sites in the city is the Temple of Heaven (*Tiantan*), located in southeastern Beijing, also a UNESCO World Heritage Site, where emperors of the Ming and Qing dynasties made visits for annual ceremonies of prayers to Heaven for good harvest.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In the north of the city is the Temple of Earth (*Ditan*), while the Temple of the Sun (*Ritan*) and the Temple of the Moon (*Yuetan*) lie in the eastern and western urban areas respectively.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Other well-known temple sites include the Dongyue Temple, Tanzhe Temple, Miaoying Temple, White Cloud Temple, Yonghe Temple, Fayuan Temple, Wanshou Temple and Big Bell Temple.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The city also has its own Confucius Temple, and a Guozijian or Imperial Academy.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception, built in 1605, is the oldest Catholic church in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Niujie Mosque is the oldest mosque in Beijing, with a history stretching back over a thousand years.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing contains several well-preserved pagodas and stone pagodas, such as the towering Pagoda of Tianning Temple, which was built during the Liao dynasty from 1100 to 1120, and the Pagoda of Cishou Temple, which was built in 1576 during the Ming dynasty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Historically noteworthy stone bridges include the 12th-century Lugou Bridge, the 17th-century Baliqiao bridge, and the 18th-century Jade Belt Bridge.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Ancient Observatory displays pre-telescopic spheres dating back to the Ming and Qing dynasties.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Fragrant Hills (*Xiangshan*) is a public park that consists of natural landscaped areas as well as traditional and cultural relics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Botanical Garden exhibits over 6,000 species of plants, including a variety of trees, bushes and flowers, and an extensive peony garden.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Taoranting, Longtan, Chaoyang, Haidian, Milu Yuan and Zizhu Yuan parks are some of the notable recreational parks in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Zoo is a center of zoological research that also contains rare animals from various continents, including the Chinese giant panda.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There are 144 museums and galleries (as of June 2008) in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Located at the outskirts of urban Beijing, but within its municipality are the Thirteen Tombs of the Ming dynasty, the lavish and elaborate burial sites of thirteen Ming emperors, which have been designated as part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site Imperial Tombs of the Ming and Qing Dynasties.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The archaeological Peking Man site at Zhoukoudian is another World Heritage Site within the municipality, containing a wealth of discoveries, among them one of the first specimens of *Homo erectus* and an assemblage of bones of the gigantic hyena *Pachycrocuta brevirostris*.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There are several sections of the UNESCO World Heritage Site Great Wall of China, most notably Badaling, Jinshanling, Simatai and Mutianyu.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to the World Travel & Tourism Council (WTTC), Beijing is the second highest earning tourist city in the world after Shanghai.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Theme parks located within the city include Universal Studios Beijing and Happy Valley Beijing, both of which are among the most visited theme parks in Asia.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The cultural heritage of Beijing is rich and diverse.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Starting 2006, the Beijing government started the process of selecting and preserving cultural heritages.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Five cultural heritage lists have been published over the years.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 288 distinct practices are categorized as cultural heritage.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] These 288 cultural heritages are further divided into ten categories, namely folk music, folk dance, traditional opera, melodious art, juggling and game, folk art, traditional handicraft, traditional medicine, folk literature and folklore.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The religious heritage of Beijing is rich and diverse as Chinese folk religion, Taoism, Buddhism, Confucianism, Islam and Christianity all have significant historical presence in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] As the national capital, the city also hosts the State Administration for Religious Affairs and various state-sponsored institutions of the leading religions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In recent decades, foreign residents have brought other religions to the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to Wang Zhiyun of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, in 2010 there were 2.2 million Buddhists in the city, equal to 11.2% of the total population.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to the Chinese General Social Survey of 2009, Christians constitute 0.78% of the city's population.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] According to a 2010 survey, Muslims constitute 1.76% of the population of Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing has many temples dedicated to folk religious and communal deities, many of which are being reconstructed or refurbished in the 2000s and 2010s.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Yearly sacrifices to the God of Heaven (祭天; *jìtiān*) at the Temple of Heaven have been resumed by Confucian groups in the 2010s.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There are temples for the worship of Taoist goddesses (娘娘; *Niángniáng*) in the city, including one primarily dedicated to Bixia Yuanjun near the Olympic Village.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Mount Miaofeng is a major center of Taoist goddess worship.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There are also many temples consecrated to the Dragon God, to the Medicine Master (药王; *Yàowáng*), to deified Guan Yu, to the Fire God (火神; *Huǒshén*), to the Wealth God, temples of the City God, and at least one temple consecrated to the Yellow Emperor (轩辕黄帝; *Xuānyuán Huángdì*) in Pinggu District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Many of these temples are governed by the Beijing Taoist Association, such as the Fire God Temple of the Shicha Lake, while many others are not and are governed by popular committees and locals.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The national Chinese Taoist Association and Chinese Taoist College have their headquarters at the White Cloud Temple of Quanzhen Taoism, which was founded in 741 and rebuilt numerous times.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Dongyue Temple outside Chaoyangmen is the largest temple of Zhengyi Taoism in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The local Beijing Taoist Association has its headquarters at the Lüzu Temple near Fuxingmen.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] 11% of the population of Beijing practices East Asian Buddhism.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Buddhist Association of China, the state's supervisory organ overseeing all Buddhist institutions in mainland China, is headquartered in the Guangji Temple, a temple founded over 800 years ago during the Jin dynasty (1115–1234) in what is now Fuchengmennei (阜成门内).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Buddhist Association along with the Buddhist Choir and Orchestra are based in the Guanghua Temple, which dates to the Yuan dynasty over 700 years ago.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Buddhist Academy of China and its library are housed in the Fayuan Temple near Caishikou.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Fayuan Temple, which dates to the Tang dynasty 1300 years ago, is the oldest temple in urban Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Tongjiao Temple inside Dongzhimen is the city's only Buddhist nunnery.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Xihuang Temple originally dates to the Liao dynasty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 1651, the temple was commissioned by the Qing Emperor Shunzhi to host the visit of the Fifth Dalai Lama to Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Since then, this temple has hosted the 13th Dalai Lama as well as the Sixth, Ninth and Tenth Panchen Lamas.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The largest Tibetan Buddhist Temple in Beijing is the Yonghe Temple, which was decreed by the Qing Emperor Qianlong in 1744 to serve as the residence and research facility for his Buddhist preceptor of Rölpé Dorjé the third Changkya (or living Buddha of Inner Mongolia).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Yonghe Temple is so-named because it was the childhood residence of the Yongzheng Emperor, and retains the glazed tiles reserved for imperial palaces.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] While the "High-level Tibetan Buddhism College of China", China's highest institution college of Tibetan Buddhism, situated near the Yonghe Temple.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Lingguang Temple of Badachu in the Western Hills also dates to the Tang dynasty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The temple's Zhaoxian Pagoda (招仙塔) was first built in 1071 during the Liao dynasty to hold a tooth relic of the Buddha.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The pagoda was destroyed during the Boxer Rebellion and the tooth was discovered from its foundation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The six aforementioned temples: Guangji, Guanghua, Tongjiao, Xihuang, Yonghe and Lingguang have been designated National Key Buddhist Temples in Han Chinese Area.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing has about 70 mosques recognized by the Islamic Association of China, whose headquarters are located next to the Niujie Mosque, the oldest mosque in the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Niujie Mosque was founded in 996 during the Liao dynasty and is frequently visited by Muslim dignitaries.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Chinese Muslim community reportedly celebrated Ramadan and made Eid prayers at the mosque in 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The largest mosque in Beijing is Changying mosque, located in Chaoyang district, with an area of 8,400 square meters.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Other notable mosques in the old city include the Dongsi Mosque, founded in 1346; the Huashi Mosque, founded in 1415; Nan Douya Mosque, near Chaoyangmen; Jinshifang Street Mosque, in Xicheng District; and the Dongzhimen Mosque.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There are large mosques in outlying Muslim communities in Haidian, Madian, Tongzhou, Changping, Changying, Shijingshan and Miyun.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The China Islamic Institute is located in the Niujie neighborhood in Xicheng District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 1289, John of Montecorvino came to Beijing as a Franciscan missionary with the order from the Pope.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] After meeting and receiving the support of Kublai Khan in 1293, he built the first Catholic church in Beijing in 1305.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association (CPCA), based in Houhai is the government oversight body for Catholics in mainland China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The National Seminary of Catholic Church in China is located in Daxing District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The earliest Protestant churches in Beijing were founded by British and American missionaries in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Protestant missionaries also opened schools, universities and hospitals which have become important civic institutions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Most of Beijing's Protestant churches were destroyed during the Boxer Rebellion and afterwards rebuilt.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 1958, the 64 Protestant churches in the city are reorganized into four and overseen by the state through the Three-Self Patriotic Movement.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] There was a significant amount of Orthodox Christians in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Orthodoxy came to Beijing with Russian prisoners from the Sino-Russian border conflicts of the 17th century.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 1956, Viktor, the bishop of Beijing returned to the Soviet Union, and the Soviet embassy took over the old cathedral and demolished it.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In 2007, the Russian embassy built a new church in its garden to serve the Russian Orthodox Christians in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Television broadcasts on channels 1 through 10, and China Central Television, China's largest television network, maintains its headquarters in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Three radio stations feature programmes in English: *Hit FM* on FM 88.7, *Easy FM* by China Radio International on FM 91.5, and the newly launched *Radio 774* on AM 774.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing Radio Stations is the family of radio stations serving the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The well-known *Beijing Evening News*, covering news about Beijing in Chinese, is distributed every afternoon.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Other newspapers include *Beijing Daily*, *The Beijing News*, the *Beijing Star Daily*, the *Beijing Morning News*, and the *Beijing Youth Daily*, as well as English-language weeklies *Beijing Weekend* and *Beijing Today*.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The *People's Daily*, *Global Times* and the *China Daily* (English) are published in Beijing as well.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Publications primarily aimed at international visitors and the expatriate community include the English-language periodicals *Time Out Beijing*, *Beijing This Month*, *Beijing Talk*, *That's Beijing*, and *The Beijinger*.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing rock (Chinese: 北京摇滚) is a wide variety of rock and roll music made by rock bands and solo artists from Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The first rock band in Beijing is Peking All-Stars, which was formed in 1979 by foreigners.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Rock bands and solo artists from Beijing include Cui Jian, Dou Wei, He Yong, Pu Shu, Tang Dynasty, Black Panther, The Flowers, 43 Baojia Street, etc.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing has hosted numerous international and national sporting events, the most notables was the 2008 Summer Olympic and Paralympic Games and the 2022 Winter Olympics and the Paralympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Other multisport international events held in Beijing include the 2001 Summer Universiade and the 1990 Asian Games.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing hosted the 2015 IAAF World Championships in Athletics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing's LeSports Center is one of the main venues for the 2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The city hosted the second Chinese National Games in 1914 and the first four National Games of China in 1959, 1965, 1975, 1979, respectively, and co-hosted the 1993 National Games with Sichuan and Qingdao.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Beijing also hosted the inaugural National Peasants' Games in 1988 and the sixth National Minority Games in 1999.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In November 2013, Beijing made a bid to host the 2022 Winter Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] On 31 July 2015, the International Olympic Committee awarded the 2022 Winter Olympics to the city becoming the first ever to host both Summer and Winter Olympics also for the 2022 Winter Paralympics becoming the first ever to host both Summer and Winter Paralympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] Major sporting venues in the city include the MasterCard Center at Wukesong west of downtown; the Workers' Stadium and Workers' Arena in Sanlitun just east of downtown and the Capital Arena in Baishiqiao, northeast of downtown.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] In addition, many universities in the city have their own sport facilities.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Olympic Green is a stadium cluster centered on the National Stadium.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] It was originally developed for the 2008 Summer Olympics and modified for the 2022 Winter Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Big Air Shougang ski jump is in the western suburbs and was built for the 2022 Winter Olympics.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] The Beijing Olympians of the American Basketball Association, formerly a Chinese Basketball Association team, kept their name and maintained a roster of primarily Chinese players after moving to Maywood, California in 2005.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p02] China Bandy Federation is based in Beijing, one of several cities in which the potential for bandy development is explored.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing is an important transport hub in North China with six ring roads, 1167 km (725 miles) of expressways, 15 National Highways, nine conventional railways, and six high-speed railways converging on the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing serves as a large rail hub in China's railway network.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In addition, the Datong–Qinhuangdao railway passes through the municipality to the north of the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing–Shenyang high-speed railway was completed in 2021.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Smaller stations in the city including Beijing East railway station and Daxing Airport station handle mainly commuter passenger traffic.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In outlying suburbs and counties of Beijing, there are over 40 railway stations.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] From Beijing, direct passenger train service is available to most large cities in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] International train service is available to Mongolia, Russia, Vietnam and North Korea.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Passenger trains in China are numbered according to their direction in relation to Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing is connected by road links to all parts of China as part of the National Trunk Road Network.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Many expressways of China serve Beijing, as do 15 China National Highways.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing's urban transport is dependent upon the ring roads that concentrically surround the city, with the Forbidden City area marked as the geographical center for the ring roads.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The ring roads appear more rectangular than ring-shaped.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The 2nd Ring Road is located in the inner city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Ring roads tend to resemble expressways progressively as they extend outwards, with the 5th and 6th Ring Roads being full-standard national expressways, linked to other roads only by interchanges.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Expressways to other regions of China are generally accessible from the 3rd Ring Road outward.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] A final outer orbital, the Capital Area Loop Expressway (G95), was fully opened in 2018 and will extend into neighboring Tianjin and Hebei.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Within the urban core, city streets generally follow the checkerboard pattern of the ancient capital.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Many of Beijing's boulevards and streets with "inner" and "outer" are still named in relation to gates in the city wall, though most gates no longer stand.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Even outside of rush hour, several roads still remain clogged with traffic.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing's urban design layout further exacerbates transportation problems.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The authorities have introduced several bus lanes, which only public buses can use during rush hour.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In the beginning of 2010, Beijing had 4 million registered automobiles.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] By the end of 2010, the government forecast 5 million.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In 2010, new car registrations in Beijing averaged 15,500 per week.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] More restrictive measures are also reserved during major events or heavily polluted weather.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] To obtain a valid license plate, Beijing drivers must be selected in a lottery.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] As part of government policy support for the use of electric vehicles, Beijing drivers with fully electric cars have a much greater chance of being selected for a license plate.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Additionally, fully electric vehicles are exempt from restrictions on which day of the week a driver may drive their vehicle.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Road signs began to be standardized with both Chinese and English names displayed, with location names using pinyin, in 2008.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing has two of the world's largest airports.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Capital International Airport (IATA: PEK), located 32 kilometres (20 mi) northeast of central Beijing in Chaoyang District bordering Shunyi District, is the second busiest airport in the world after Atlanta's Hartsfield–Jackson International Airport.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Capital Airport's Terminal 3, built during the expansion for the 2008 Olympics, is one of the largest in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Capital Airport is the main hub for Air China and Hainan Airlines.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Airport Expressway and Second Airport Expressway connects the airport to the northeast and east of the city center, respectively.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Driving time from city center is about 40 minutes under normal traffic conditions.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Capital Airport Express line of Beijing Subway and the Capital Airport Bus serves the Beijing Capital International Airport.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Daxing International Airport (IATA: PKX) located 46 kilometres (29 mi) south of the city in Daxing District bordering the city of Langfang, Hebei Province, opened on 25 September 2019.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Daxing Airport has one of the world's largest terminal buildings and is expected to be a major airport serving Beijing, Tianjin and northern Hebei Province.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Daxing Airport is connected to the city via the Beijing–Xiong'an intercity railway, the Daxing Airport Express line of the Beijing Subway and two expressways.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] With the opening of the Daxing Airport in September 2019, the Beijing Nanyuan Airport (IATA: NAY), located 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) south of center in Fengtai District, has been closed to civilian airline service.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Other airports in the city at Liangxiang, Xijiao, Shahe and Badaling are primarily for military use.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] As of June 2026, visitors from 53 countries are permitted a 240-hour visa-free transit visit in Beijing, where the 240 hours is calculated from midnight of the day after entry and visitors are only permitted to stay within Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Nationals from 50 countries are also permitted a 30-day visa-free stay in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Subway, which began operating in 1969, now has 25 lines, 459 stations, and 783 km (487 mi) of lines.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] It is the longest subway system in the world and first in annual ridership with 3.66 billion rides delivered in 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In 2013, with a flat fare of ¥2.00 (US$0.31) per ride with unlimited transfers on all lines except the Airport Express, the subway was also the most affordable rapid transit system in China.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The subway is undergoing rapid expansion and is expected to reach 30 lines, 450 stations, 1,050 kilometres (650 mi) in length by 2022.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] When fully implemented, 95% of residents inside the Fourth Ring Road will be able to walk to a station in 15 minutes.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Suburban Railway provides commuter rail service to outlying suburbs of the municipality.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] As part of the urban re-development for the 2008 Olympics, Beijing's subway system was significantly expanded.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] On 28 December 2014, it switched to a distance-based fare system from a fixed fare for all lines except the Airport Express.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Under the new system a trip under 6 km (3+1⁄2 mi) will cost ¥3.00(US$0.49), an additional ¥1.00 will be added for the next 6 km (3+1⁄2 mi) and the next 10 km (6 mi) until the distance for the trip reaches 32 km (20 mi).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] For every 20 kilometres (12 miles) after the original 32 kilometres (20 miles) an additional ¥1.00 is added.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] For example, a 50-kilometre (31-mile) trip would cost ¥ 8.00.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] There are nearly 1,000 public bus and trolleybus lines in the city, including four bus rapid transit lines.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Standard bus fares are as low as ¥1.00 when purchased with the *Yikatong* metrocard.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Most taxis are Hyundai Elantras, Hyundai Sonatas, Peugeots, Citroëns and Volkswagen Jettas.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] After 15 kilometres (9.3 mi), the base fare increases by 50% (but is only applied to the portion *over* that distance).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Different companies have special colours combinations painted on their vehicles.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Usually registered taxis have yellowish brown as basic hue, with another color of Prussian blue, hunter green, white, umber, tyrian purple, rufous, or sea green.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Between 11 pm and 5 am, there is also a 20% fee increase.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Rides over 15 km (9 mi) and between 23:00 and 06:00 incur both charges, for a total increase of 80%.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Tolls during trip should be covered by customers and the costs of trips beyond Beijing city limits should be negotiated with the driver.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The cost of unregistered taxis is also subject to negotiation with the driver.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing has long been well known for the number of bicycles on its streets.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Although the rise of motor traffic has created a great deal of congestion and bicycle use has declined, bicycles are still an important form of local transportation.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Many cyclists can be seen on most roads in the city, and most of the main roads have dedicated bicycle lanes.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing is relatively flat, which makes cycling convenient.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The rise of electric bicycles and electric scooters, which have similar speeds and use the same cycle lanes, may have brought about a revival in bicycle-speed two-wheeled transport.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] It is possible to cycle to most parts of the city.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Because of the growing traffic congestion, the authorities have indicated more than once that they wish to encourage cycling, but it is not clear whether there is sufficient will to translate that into action on a significant scale.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] On 30 March 2019, a 6.5 km (4 mile) bicycle-dedicated lane was opened, easing the traffic congestion between Huilongguan and Shangdi where there are many high-tech companies.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Cycling has seen a resurgence in popularity spurred by the emergence of a large number of dockless app based bikeshares such as Mobike, Bluegogo and Ofo since 2016.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The command headquarters of China's military forces are based in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Central Military Commission, the political organ in charge of the military, is housed inside the Ministry of National Defense, located next to the Military Museum of the Chinese People's Revolution in western Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Rocket Force, which controls the country's strategic missile and nuclear weapons, has its command in Qinghe, Haidian District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The headquarters of the Central Theater Command, one of five nationally, is based further west in Gaojing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The CTR oversees the Beijing Capital Garrison as well as the 81st, 82nd and 83rd Armies, which are based in Hebei.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The China National Space Administration, which oversees country's space program, and several space-related state owned companies, such as CASTC and CASIC, are all based in Beijing.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Aerospace Command and Control Center, in Haidian District, tracks the country's crewed and uncrewed flight and other space exploration initiatives.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing's municipal territory encompasses a diverse range of ecosystems, including montane forests in the west and north, plains, wetlands, and river valleys.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] As of 2022, the city had achieved a forest coverage rate of 44.8 percent and an urban green coverage rate of 49.3 percent.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Forest coverage has expanded dramatically since 1949, when it stood at just 1.3 percent.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] A biodiversity survey conducted between 2020 and 2024 documented 7,121 species across multiple categories, including higher plants, vertebrates, insects, and macro fungi, within 151 natural and semi-natural ecosystem types.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The city is home to 608 species of wild terrestrial vertebrates and 2,088 species of plants, and hosts 515 species of wild birds, an increase of nearly 100 species over the preceding decade.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Among the capitals of G20 nations, Beijing ranks second in bird species diversity.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing Municipality has 20 nature reserves, with a combined area of 1,339.7 km2 (517.3 sq mi).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The mountains to the west and north of the city are home to a number of protected wildlife species including leopard, leopard cat, wolf, red fox, wild boar, masked palm civet, raccoon dog, hog badger, Siberian weasel, Amur hedgehog, roe deer, and mandarin rat snake.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The Beijing Aquatic Wildlife Rescue and Conservation Center protects the Chinese giant salamander, Amur stickleback, and mandarin duck on the Huaijiu and Huaisha Rivers in Huairou District.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] To the south of the city, the Beijing Milu Park is home to one of the largest herds of Père David's deer, which are now extinct in the wild.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Endemic to Beijing is the Beijing barbastelle, a species of vesper bat discovered in caves of Fangshan District in 2001 and identified as a distinct species in 2007.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The mountains of Fangshan are also the natural habitat for the more common Beijing mouse-eared bat, large myotis, greater horseshoe bat, and Rickett's big-footed bat.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Each year, Beijing hosts 200–300 species of migratory birds including the common crane, black-headed gull, swan, mallard, common cuckoo, and the endangered yellow-breasted bunting.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In May 2016, Common cuckoos nesting in the wetlands of Cuihu (Haidian), Hanshiqiao (Shunyi), Yeyahu (Yanqing) were tagged and have been traced as far as India, Kenya and Mozambique.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In the fall of 2016, the Beijing Forest Police undertook a month-long campaign to crack down on illegal hunting and trapping of migratory birds for sale in local bird markets.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Over 1,000 rescued birds of protected species including streptopelia, Eurasian siskin, crested myna, coal tit, and great tit were handed to the Beijing Wildlife Protection and Rescue Center for repatriation to the wild.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The city flowers are the Chinese rose and chrysanthemum.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The city trees are the Chinese arborvitae (an evergreen in the cypress family) and the pagoda tree (a deciduous tree in the bean family, also called the Chinese scholar tree).
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] The oldest scholar tree in the city was planted in what is now Beihai Park during the Tang dynasty.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] Beijing is also home to the headquarters of the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO), making it an important city for international diplomacy.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] In 2019, China had the largest diplomatic network in the world.
[src:howstuffworks/beijing-china-p03] China hosts a large diplomatic community in its capital city of Beijing; as of 2020, the Chinese capital hosts 173 embassies, one consulate and three representatives, excluding the trade offices of Hong Kong and Macau.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The website was acquired by Discovery Communications in 2007, but was sold to Blucora in 2014.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The site has since expanded out into podcasting, focusing on factual topics.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In December 2016, HowStuffWorks, LLC became a subsidiary of OpenMail, LLC, later renamed System1.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 2018, the podcast division of the company, which had been spun-off by System1 under the name Stuff Media, was acquired by iHeartMedia for $55 million.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 1998, then North Carolina State University instructor Marshall Brain (1961–2024), started the site as a hobby.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 1999, Brain raised venture capital and formed HowStuffWorks, Inc.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In March 2002, HowStuffWorks was sold to the Convex Group, an Atlanta-based investment and media company founded by Jeff Arnold, founder and former chief executive officer (CEO) of WebMD.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The headquarters moved from Cary, North Carolina, to Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] HowStuffWorks originally focused on science and machines, ranging from submarines to common household gadgets and appliances.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] After adding a staff of writers, artists, and editors, content expanded to a larger array of topics.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] On October 20, 2004, Stuffo.com was created, and HowStuffWorks moved its entertainment section over to the new website.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The domain HowStuffWorks.com attracted at least 58 million visitors annually by 2008, according to a Compete.com survey.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] There have been four HowStuffWorks books—two illustrated hardcover coffee table books, *HowStuffWorks* and *More HowStuffWorks*, and two un-illustrated paperbacks, *How Much Does the Earth Weigh?* and *What If?*.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] HowStuffWorks previously put out an educational magazine, *HowStuffWorks Express*, for middle-school students.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The company has also released a series of HowStuffWorks trivia "LidRock" discs—CD-ROMs sold on fountain drink lids at Regal Theaters.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 2005, HowStuffWorks became the exclusive online publisher for Publications International, Ltd., Consumer Guide and Mobil Travel Guide.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] Howstuffworks.com spun off its international division when it went public (Nasdaq:HSWI) via an acquisition of INTAC, a China-based company.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In March 2007, HSW International launched its Portuguese website with headquarters in São Paulo, Brazil.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The Portuguese name of the site is Como Tudo Funciona ("how everything works").
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In June 2008, the Chinese site was launched with new headquarters in Beijing, China.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The URL roughly translates to "Knowledge Information Web".
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] On October 15, 2007, Discovery Communications announced it had bought HowStuffWorks for $250 million.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The company later chose to use the name HowStuffWorks as the title of a television series on its Discovery Channel.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] The series, which focuses on commodities, premiered in November 2008 and is similar in style and content to other "how it works" programs, like *Modern Marvels*.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] On November 2, 2009, HSW International co-founded Sharecare, developing a social QA platform through which users ask health and wellness-related questions, receiving answers from industry experts.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] Other co-founders in Sharecare include Jeff Arnold, Dr.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] Mehmet Oz, Harpo Productions, Discovery Communications, and Sony Pictures Television.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] On April 21, 2014, Discovery Communications announced that it had sold HowStuffWorks to Blucora for $45 million.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In July 2016, Blucora announced the sale of its Infospace business, including HowStuffWorks, to OpenMail for $45 million.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 2014, HowStuffWorks moved its headquarters from Buckhead to Ponce City Market, a new mixed-use development in the Old Fourth Ward neighborhood of Atlanta.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In June 2017, it announced the hiring of Cracked.com founder and former editor-in-chief Jack O'Brien for its new comedy podcasting division.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In 2017, System1 spun off the podcast department of HowStuffWorks as Stuff Media, retaining the HowStuffWorks website.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] In September 2018, Stuff Media announced its sale to radio broadcaster iHeartMedia for $55 million.
[src:howstuffworks/howstuffworks] HowStuffWorks maintained a large number of podcasts, hosted by its staff writers and editors, but now all former HSW podcasts are owned and operated by iHeartRadio.
